# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chief-executive-officer
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] An **account manager** (**AM**) is a person who works for a company and is responsible for the management of sales and relationships with particular customers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] An account manager maintains the company's existing relationships with a client or group of clients, so that they will continue using the company for business.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Account managers do not manage the daily running of the account.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] They manage the relationship with the client of the account(s) they are assigned to.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Generally, a client will remain with one account manager throughout the account's duration.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Account managers serve as the interface between customer service and the sales team in a company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] They are assigned a company's existing client accounts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The purpose of being assigned particular clients is to create long term client relationships.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The account manager serves to understand the customer's demands, plan how to meet these demands, and generate sales for the company as a result.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The responsibilities of account managers can vary depending on the industry they work in, size of the company and nature of the business.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Each customer account can vary in demands and an account manager may work with brand managers for one account and a media department for another.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Account managers usually report directly to the account director or agency director of the activity and status of accounts and transactions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] An account manager may also manage a single account or a variety of accounts depending on the requirement of the company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Manage and solve conflicts with clients The Account Manager is expected to have specific information regarding the daily operations of the company and keep the Client updated.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] There are situations in which an account manager, for example in advertising firms, is responsible for more than one account and therefore looks after multiple clients.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] When account locations do not overlap the account manager can be placed at the divisional, district, or territory level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] When a sales team has a senior sales manager, the account manager coordinates sales accounts from other departments or specialties.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] In this scenario, the sales team will work under the direct supervision of influencers and deciders instead of with a buyer.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Global account managers and national account managers may work together in a hierarchical or matrix structure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The trend is to move responsibility for the major key accounts to the global level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] A key account manager (KAM) is assigned to a company headquarters to oversee the account team assigned to a particular account.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Key account management includes sales but also includes planning and managing the full relationship between a business and its most important customers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] An account manager who works in this role will engage in a variety of tasks including project management, coordination, strategic planning, relationship management, negotiation, leadership and innovative development of opportunities, and keeping record of transactions of sale and purchase goods.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The tasks may include working with product design and application, logistics, sales support, and marketing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] The basic assumption for a key account management model is the correct classification of the key accounts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] A basic model often used from 1950 to 1970 was the classification model of Webster.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] This model has been adapted by Milman and Wilson into a two-dimensional model and was paramount from 1970 to 1990.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Bensaou has tested this model empirically by his research of carmakers in the United States and Japan and made revisions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] De Blick synthesized the adaptations into the 4S-model, a key account classification model.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] By the late 1990s, key account management spread to most B2B (business-to-business) models.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Account managers can work for small or large companies either corporate, financial, retail, or government for instance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Any company with a specific set of clients they conduct business with, can employ an account manager.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Account managers usually work in an office setting and can work more than 40 hours weekly.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Travel is usually included in the job description.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] National or global account managers will very likely experience extra travel.
[src:chief-executive-officer/account-manager] Although personality and an aptitude for sales is key, a degree in business, marketing, or related field is typically required and depending on the nature of the account, a background in marketing or media studies may be preferred.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The **administrative geography of the United Kingdom** is intricate, layered, and inconsistent across its constituent nations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The country also has complex and inconsistent municipal structure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] As a sovereign state located northwest of continental Europe, the United Kingdom comprises England, Northern Ireland, Scotland, and Wales.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Each of these nations operates its own distinct system of local government and territorial divisions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] As a result, there is no single, unified layer of administrative units that spans the entire United Kingdom.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] As there is no written document that comprehensively encompasses the British constitution, and owing to a convoluted history of the formation of the United Kingdom, a variety of terms are used to refer to its constituent parts, which are sometimes called the four countries of the United Kingdom.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The four are sometimes collectively referred to as the Home Nations, particularly in sporting contexts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Although the four countries are important for legal and governmental purposes, they are not comparable to administrative subdivisions of most other countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom also contains 17 dependent territories which are not officially a part of the UK but are represented by it in places like the UN.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Historically, the subnational divisions of the UK have been the county and the ecclesiastical parish, while following the emergence of a unified parliament of the United Kingdom, the ward and constituency have been pan-UK political subdivisions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] More contemporary divisions include Lieutenancy areas and the statistical territories defined with the modern International Territorial Level (formerly NUTS) and ISO 3166-2:GB systems.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The independence of the Irish Free State in 1922, following the partition of Ireland, resulted in the present-day United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Wales was incorporated into the English legal system through the Laws in Wales Acts 1535-1542, the earlier Statute of Rhuddlan having restricted but not abolished Welsh Law following the Edwardian conquest in 1282.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] As a result, England and Wales are treated as a single entity for some purposes, principally that they share a legal system (see English law), while Scotland and Northern Ireland each have a separate legal system (see Scots Law and Northern Ireland law).
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Northern Ireland was the first part of the British Isles to have a devolved government, under the *Government of Ireland Act 1920*, and that continued until the Parliament of Northern Ireland was suspended in 1972.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] After a period of direct rule by the Westminster government and some abortive attempts at reinstating devolved government during the Troubles, the present-day Northern Ireland Assembly was established in 1998, and is currently in operation following a number of periods of suspension.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The complex history of Northern Ireland has led to differing views as to its status.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The term "Province" is often used by unionist and British commentators to refer to Northern Ireland, but not by nationalists.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Following Brexit the UK ONS replaced the EU NUTS1 regional model with its own International Territorial Level model, continuing the treatment of the 3 Home Nations alongside the 9 Regions of England.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The markers above link to relevant articles where available.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Can have city, town, village or neighbourhood status.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Not all areas of England have parishes, especially metropolitan areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] County council areas comprising one district.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The council is at either county or district level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] England has no devolved national legislature or government.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Matters devolved to the devolved administrations in Wales, Scotland and Northern Ireland are held by Parliament and executed by the UK Government.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] England itself has an intricate, layered, and inconsistent system of administrative divisions, which largely originate from the major restructuring of local government in 1972.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Outside the London region and the Isles of Scilly, the entirety of England is divided into counties and districts of local government purposes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Local government counties are either classified as metropolitan or non-metropolitan.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] While every area is legally part of a county, all metropolitan counties and some non-metropolitan counties do not have any administrative body; in these cases, the functions that would otherwise be undertaken by a county council are instead undertaken by a single, or untiary, authority.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] London conversely is divided into 32 boroughs, which make up Greater London, and the City of London, which has unique (Sui generis) governance arrangements compared to the rest of England.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] London also has the Greater London Authority, and a directly elected Mayor of London.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The Isles of Scilly also have unique governance arrangements.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] County, district and unitary authorities are sometimes grouped with London borough councils and the Isle of Scilly council as principal authorities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] In many areas, there are civil parishes with parish or town councils.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Parished areas cover most of England but they are not universal and are not as common in larger urban areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Areas not within a civil parish are called unparished areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Some areas sit within a combined authority area.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] A combined authority is not a local authority in its own right, but an established legal body that covers multiple principal local authority areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] In some cases, these align with a local government county (e.g.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Greater Manchester) or otherwise combine multiple districts and counties together.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Other cooperative structures that span local government areas, like joint local planning or waste collection, informally create additional local government geographies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Some local services, such as policing, fire and rescue and health, are delivered along different geographical lines than the area a principal local authority covers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] In this case, the service will be delivered by a different authority from the principal local authority.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Northern Ireland has the Northern Ireland Assembly and Northern Ireland Executive established under the Good Friday Agreement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] During periods where the devolved institutions were suspended, executive government in Northern Ireland was administered directly by the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland and laws made in the United Kingdom Parliament – known as *"direct rule"* in contrast to devolution.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] For local government, Northern Ireland is divided into 11 districts, which are unitary authorities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Northern Ireland is divided into six traditional counties.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Though widely used, these no longer serve any administrative purpose.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Scotland has a devolved legislature, the Scottish Parliament, with a government, the Scottish Government, since 1999.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The Scottish Government is headed by the First Minister of Scotland who is responsible for all areas of decision making, government policy as well as the international engagement of Scotland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The Scottish Parliament is made up of 129 elected Members of the Scottish Parliament (MSPs), with the population of Scotland being represented by a number of 8 MSPs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The Scottish Parliament consists of two types of MSPs – a constituency MSP who represents the local area, and seven regional list MSPs who collectively represent the larger area that includes any given constituency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The Scottish Parliament meets at Holyrood, located in the capital city of Edinburgh.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Edinburgh is also the seat of Bute House, the official residence of the First Minister, as well as the Palace of Holyroodhouse, the official residence of the monarch in Scotland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The highest courts in Scotland operating under the countries legal system – the High Court of Justiciary and the Court of Session (known collectively as the Supreme Courts of Scotland) – are based at Parliament House, Edinburgh.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] For local government, Scotland has 32 council areas (unitary authorities).
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Below this uniform level of subdivision, there are varying levels of area committees in the larger rural council areas, and many small community councils throughout the country, although these are not universal.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Scottish community councils have few if any powers beyond being a forum for raising issues of concern.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Wales has an elected, devolved legislature, the Senedd (Welsh Parliament; Welsh: *Senedd Cymru*), from which the Welsh Government is drawn.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] For local government, Wales consists of 22 unitary principal areas, split equally into 11 county boroughs and 11 counties, although 4 principal areas also hold city status.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Below these are community councils, which have powers similar to those of English parish councils.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The 22 principal areas are grouped into preserved counties, which are used for ceremonial purposes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Although based on the counties used for local government between 1974 and 1996, they no longer have an administrative function.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Each of the 650 electoral areas or divisions called constituencies of the Parliament of the United Kingdom has, since 1950, elected one Member of Parliament (MP) to represent it at the House of Commons of the United Kingdom.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Before 1950, some constituencies elected two or more MPs using the plurality bloc vote system, and before the Reform Act 1832 nearly all constituencies in England returned two MPs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The devolved Scottish Parliament, the Welsh Senedd both use an additional member system of elections, which combines single-member constituencies with multi-member electoral regions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Elections to the Northern Ireland Assembly are held under the single transferable vote (STV) system, in 18 multi-member constituencies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The wards and electoral divisions of the United Kingdom are electoral districts at subnational level represented by one or more councillors at local authority level, or else used to divide the electorate into electoral districts for voting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] It is the primary unit of British electoral geography.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] There are also many informal, historical and special purpose regional designations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Some such as the Highlands of Scotland have or have had, to some extent, formal boundaries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Others such as the London commuter belt are more diffuse.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Some such as Snowdonia (Welsh: *Eryri*) have a formal boundary in some contexts; in this case as a National Park.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Others such as The Fens of eastern England are quite distinctly defined by geography but do not form any official entity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The UK's Office for National Statistics, the International Organization for Standardization and before 2021 Eurostat, have developed subdivision codes for the UK.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The United Kingdom has 17 dependent territories in total: three "Crown Dependencies" in the British Isles and in the English Channel and fourteen "overseas territories" scattered around the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Unlike other former colonial powers, the British Government does not classify its overseas possessions (or the crown dependencies, which share historical ties with the British Crown) as subdivisions of the United Kingdom itself; rather, each is treated in law as a separate jurisdiction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Most have their own legislatures and a degree of autonomy usually exceeding that of the devolved UK nations, including fiscal independence.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] Out of the 14 overseas territories, 10 are autonomous, two used primarily as military bases, one uninhabited, and one an Antarctic claim.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] However, the UK retains varying degrees of responsibility in all of the territories, currently ranging from full political control to a largely ceremonial presence.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The main reserved matters are the areas of diplomacy, international treaties, defence and security.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The UK also retains in all territories a residual responsibility for 'good governance', a loosely defined constitutional concept recently exemplified by its imposition of direct rule following alleged serious corruption in the Turks and Caicos Islands.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The UK parliament at Westminster, and the British Government through the Privy Council, both retain the power to legislate for the overseas territories – though by convention will usually only do so with each local government's consent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] The three Crown Dependencies within the British Isles are self-governing possessions of the British Crown.
[src:chief-executive-officer/administrative-geography-of-the-united-kingdom] They are distinct from the British overseas territories of the United Kingdom.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, during the Last Glacial Period.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] By the time of British settlement, Aboriginal Australians spoke more than 250 distinct languages and had one of the oldest living cultures in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's written history commenced with Dutch exploration of most of the coastline in the 17th century.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] British colonisation began in 1788 with the establishment of the penal colony of New South Wales.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] By the mid-19th century, most of the continent had been explored by European settlers and five additional self-governing British colonies were established, each gaining responsible government by 1890.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The colonies federated in 1901, forming the Commonwealth of Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] This continued a process of increasing autonomy from the United Kingdom, highlighted by the *Statute of Westminster Adoption Act 1942*, and culminating in the *Australia Act 1986*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is a parliamentary democracy with a constitutional monarchy, and a federation comprising six states and ten territories.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Its population of almost 29 million is highly urbanised and heavily concentrated on the eastern seaboard.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Canberra is the nation's capital, while its most populous cities are Sydney and Melbourne, each with a population of more than five million.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's culture is diverse, and the country has one of the highest foreign-born populations in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It has a highly developed economy and one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Its abundant natural resources and well-developed international trade relations are crucial to the country's economy.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It ranks highly for quality of life, health, education, economic freedom, civil liberties and political rights.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, and has the world's thirteenth-highest military expenditure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is a member of international groups including: the United Nations, the G20, the OECD, the World Trade Organization, Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community and the Commonwealth of Nations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia also participates in the defence, intelligence and security alliances ANZUS, AUKUS and Five Eyes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The name *Australia* (pronounced /əˈstreɪliə/ in Australian English) is derived from the Latin *Terra Australis Incognita* ('unknown southern land'), a name used for a hypothetical continent in the Southern Hemisphere since ancient times.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Several 16th-century cartographers used the word *Australia* on maps, but not to identify modern Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] When the Dutch began visiting and mapping Australia in the 17th century, they called the continent *New Holland*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The name *Australia* was popularised by the explorer Matthew Flinders, who circumnavigated the continent in 1803.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] However, when his account of his voyage was published in 1814, the name *Terra Australis* was used.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Governor of New South Wales Lachlan Macquarie officially recommended the name *Australia* to replace *New Holland* in December 1817.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The British Admiralty adopted the name in 1824, and the British Parliament used it in legislation in 1828.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The United Kingdom Hydrographic Office used the new name in *The Australia Directory* of 1830.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The name "Commonwealth of Australia" for the new federation of the six former colonies was formalised in the *Commonwealth of Australia Constitution Act 1900* (UK).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Colloquial names for Australia include "Oz", "Straya" and "Down Under".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Human habitation of the Australian continent is estimated to have begun 50,000 to 65,000 years ago, with the migration of people by land bridges and short sea crossings from what is now Southeast Asia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is uncertain how many waves of immigration may have contributed to these ancestors of modern Aboriginal Australians.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Madjedbebe rock shelter in Arnhem Land is possibly the oldest site showing the presence of humans in Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The oldest human remains found are the Lake Mungo remains, which have been dated to approximately 42,000 years ago.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australian culture is one of the oldest continuous cultures on Earth.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] At the time of first European contact, Aboriginal Australians belonged to wide range of societies, with diverse economies spread across at least 250 different language groups.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Estimates of the Aboriginal population before British settlement range from 300,000 to 3 million.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Aboriginal Australians cultures were (and remain) deeply connected with the land and the environment, with stories of The Dreaming maintained through oral tradition, songs, dance and paintings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Certain groups engaged in fire-stick farming, fish farming, and built semi-permanent shelters.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] These practices have variously been characterised as "hunter-gatherer", "agricultural", "natural cultivation" and "intensification".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Torres Strait Islander people first settled their islands at least 2,500 years ago.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Culturally and linguistically distinct from mainland Aboriginal peoples, they were seafarers and obtained their livelihood from seasonal horticulture and the resources of their reefs and seas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Agriculture also developed on some islands and villages appeared by the 1300s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] By the mid-18th century in northern Australia, contact, trade and cross-cultural engagement had been established between local Aboriginal groups and Makassan trepangers, visiting from present-day Indonesia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 1606 the crew of the Dutch ship, *Duyfken*, captained by Willem Janszoon, made the first documented European landing in Australia and contact with Aboriginal Australians.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Later that year, Luís Vaz de Torres sailed to the north of Australia through Torres Strait, along New Guinea's southern coast.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Abel Tasman's voyage of 1642 was the first known European expedition to reach Van Diemen's Land.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] On his second voyage of 1644, he mapped the north coast of Australia south of New Guinea.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Following Tasman's voyages, the Dutch were able to make almost complete maps of Australia's northern and western coasts and much of its southern and south-eastern Tasmanian coasts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 1770, Captain James Cook sailed along and mapped the east coast, which he named "New South Wales" and claimed for Great Britain.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 1786, the British government announced its intention to establish a penal colony in New South Wales.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] On 26 January 1788, the First Fleet commanded by Captain Arthur Phillip, arrived at Sydney Cove, Port Jackson.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] A camp was established and the Union Flag raised and the date later became Australia's national day.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Most early settlers were convicts, transported for petty crimes and assigned as labourers or servants to "free settlers" (willing immigrants).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Once emancipated, convicts tended to integrate into colonial society.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Aboriginal resistance, convict rebellions and bushranging were sometimes suppressed under martial law.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The 1808 Rum Rebellion, carried out by officers of the New South Wales Corp, led to a temporary military junta.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] During the next two decades, social and economic reforms, together with the establishment of a Legislative Council and Supreme Court, saw the penal colony transition to a civil society.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The indigenous population declined for 150 years following European settlement, mainly due to infectious disease.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] British colonial authorities did not sign any treaties with Aboriginal groups.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As settlement expanded, tens of thousands of Indigenous people and thousands of settlers were killed in frontier conflicts, which many historians argue included acts of genocide by settlers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Settlers dispossessed surviving Indigenous peoples of most of their land.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 1803, a settlement was established in Van Diemen's Land (present-day Tasmania), and in 1813, Gregory Blaxland, William Lawson and William Wentworth crossed the Blue Mountains west of Sydney, opening the interior to European settlement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The British claim was extended to the whole Australian continent in 1827 when Major Edmund Lockyer established a settlement on King George Sound (modern-day Albany).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Swan River Colony (present-day Perth) was established in 1829, evolving into the largest Australian colony by area, Western Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Separate colonies were carved from New South Wales: Tasmania in 1825, South Australia in 1836, Victoria in 1851, and Queensland in 1859.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] South Australia and Victoria were founded as free colonies – they never accepted transported convicts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Growing opposition to the convict system culminated in its abolition in the eastern colonies by the 1850s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Initially a free colony, Western Australia accepted convicts from 1850 to 1868.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The six colonies individually gained responsible government between 1855 and 1890, managing most of their own affairs while remaining part of the British Empire.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Colonial Office in London retained control of some matters, notably foreign affairs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The colonial parliaments progressively extended voting rights to adult men from 1856, with women's suffrage on equal terms following between the 1890s and 1900s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Some colonies introduced racial restrictions on voting from 1885.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In the mid-19th century, explorers such as Burke and Wills charted Australia's interior.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] A series of gold rushes beginning in the early 1850s led to an influx of new migrants from China, North America and continental Europe, as well as outbreaks of bushranging and civil unrest; the latter peaked in 1854 when Ballarat miners launched the Eureka Rebellion against gold licence fees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The 1860s saw the rise of blackbirding, where South Sea Islanders were coerced or abducted into indentured labour, mainly by Queensland colonists.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] From 1886, Australian colonial governments began removing many Aboriginal children from their families and communities, justified on the grounds of child protection and forced assimilation policies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Second Boer War (1899–1902) marked the largest overseas deployment of Australia's colonial forces.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] On 1 January 1901, federation of the colonies was achieved after a decade of planning, constitutional conventions and referendums, resulting in the establishment of the Commonwealth of Australia as a nation under the new Australian Constitution.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] From 1901, Australia was a self-governing dominion within the British Empire.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It was one of the founding members of the League of Nations in 1920, and the United Nations in 1945.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The *Statute of Westminster 1931* ended the ability of the UK to legislate for Australia at the federal level without Australia's consent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia adopted it in 1942, but it was backdated to 1939 to confirm the validity of legislation passed during World War II.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian Capital Territory was formed in 1911 as the location for the future federal capital of Canberra.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] While it was being constructed, Melbourne served as the temporary capital from 1901 to 1927.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Northern Territory was transferred from South Australia to the Commonwealth in 1911.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia took over the administration of the Territory of Papua (previously British New Guinea) in 1905 and of the Territory of New Guinea (formerly German New Guinea) in 1920.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The two were unified as the Territory of Papua and New Guinea in 1949 and gained independence from Australia in 1975.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 1914, Australia joined the Allies in the First World War, and took part in the fighting on several fronts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Of the 324,000 men who served overseas, about 60,000 were killed and another 152,000 were wounded.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Many Australians regard the defeat of the Australian and New Zealand Army Corps (ANZAC) at Gallipoli in 1915 as the "baptism of fire" that forged the new nation's identity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The beginning of the campaign is commemorated annually on Anzac Day, a date which rivals Australia Day as the nation's most important.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] From 1939 to 1945, Australia joined the Allies in fighting the Second World War.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's armed forces fought in the Pacific, European and Mediterranean and Middle East theatres.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Since 1951, Australia has maintained a mutual security alliance with the United States under the ANZUS treaty.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In the three decades following World War II, Australia experienced significant increases in living standards, leisure time and suburban development.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Governments encouraged a large wave of immigration from across Europe and called these migrants "New Australians".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] High immigration was justified to Australians using the slogan "populate or perish", and from the 1960s the white Australia policy was gradually relaxed.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] A member of the Western Bloc during the Cold War, Australia participated in the Korean War and the Malayan Emergency during the 1950s and the Vietnam War from 1962 to 1973.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Tensions over communist influence in society led to unsuccessful attempts by the Menzies Government to ban the Communist Party of Australia, and a bitter split in the Labor Party in 1955.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As a result of a 1967 referendum, the federal government gained the power to legislate with regard to Aboriginal Australians, and Aboriginal Australians were fully included in the census.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Pre-colonial land interests (referred to as native title in Australia) was recognised in law for the first time when the High Court of Australia held in *Mabo v Queensland (No 2)* that Australia was not *terra nullius* ('land belonging to no one') at the time of European settlement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Following the abolition of the last vestiges of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia's demography and culture transformed as a result of a large and ongoing wave of non-European immigration, mostly from Asia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The late 20th century also saw an increasing focus on foreign policy ties with other Asia–Pacific nations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australia Acts of 1986 severed the remaining constitutional ties between Australia and the United Kingdom while maintaining the monarch in her independent capacity as Queen of Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In a 1999 constitutional referendum, 55% of voters rejected abolishing the monarchy and becoming a republic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Following the September 11 attacks in the United States, Australia joined the United States in fighting the Afghanistan War from 2001 to 2021 and the Iraq War from 2003 to 2009.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The nation's trade relations also became increasingly oriented towards East Asia in the 21st century, with China becoming the nation's largest trading partner by a large margin.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In response to the COVID-19 pandemic, from March 2020 lockdowns and other restrictions on public gatherings and movement across the national and state borders were implemented by the Federal, state and territory governments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Following the rollout of vaccines in 2021, these restrictions were gradually eased.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In October 2023, Australia declared that COVID-19 was no longer a communicable disease incident of national significance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia consists of the mainland Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, numerous smaller offshore islands, and the remote offshore territories of Ashmore and Cartier Islands, Christmas Island, Cocos (Keeling) Islands, Coral Sea Islands, Heard and McDonald Islands, and Norfolk Island.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia also claims about 42% of Antarctica as the Australian Antarctic Territory, but this claim is only recognised by four other countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Mainland Australia lies between latitudes 9° and 44° south, and longitudes 112° and 154° east.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Surrounded by the Indian and Pacific oceans, Australia is separated from Asia by the Arafura and Timor seas, with the Coral Sea lying off the Queensland coast, and the Tasman Sea lying between Australia and New Zealand.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Great Barrier Reef, the world's largest coral reef, lies a short distance off the north-east coast and extends for more than 2,300 km (1,400 mi).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The mainland is the world's smallest continent and the country is the sixth-largest by total area.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is sometimes considered the world's largest island and is often dubbed the "island continent".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It has 35,877 km (22,293 mi) of coastline (excluding all offshore islands), and claims an exclusive economic zone of 8,148,250 square kilometres (3,146,060 sq mi).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] This exclusive economic zone does not include the Australian Antarctic Territory.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2021, Australia had 10% of the global permanent meadows and pastureland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Forest cover is about 17% of Australia's land area.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian mainland is relatively flat, with an average height of 325 metres (1,066 ft) compared with 870 metres (2,850 ft) for all continents.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Great Dividing Range runs along most of eastern Australia, dividing the central lowlands from the eastern highlands.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] At 2,228 m (7,310 ft), Mount Kosciuszko is the highest mountain on the mainland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Taller are Mawson Peak, at 2,745 m (9,006 ft), on Heard Island, and, in the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mount McClintock and Mount Menzies, at 3,492 m (11,457 ft) and 3,355 m (11,007 ft) respectively.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Murray-Darling is the major river system, draining most of inland New South Wales and Southern Queensland towards Lake Alexandrina and the sea in South Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There are also smaller coastal river systems, inland drainage systems such as the Lake Eyre system, and salt lake systems in central and western Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's rivers have the lowest discharge into the sea of any continent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The mainland's flat, arid profile also makes its rivers slow-moving, resulting in a build up of salt on the land.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Salinisation adversely affects Australia's soil which is, on average, poor in nutrients compared with world standards.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's population is concentrated on the coastal fringes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] About 95% of the population lives within 100 km of the coast; the world average is 39%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's population density is 3.5 inhabitants per square kilometre, which is one of the lowest in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] However, there is a large concentration of the population in cities along the temperate south-eastern coastline, and population density exceeds 38 inhabitants per square kilometre in central Melbourne.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Formerly part of the Rodinia and Gondwana supercontinents, Australia completely separated from Antarctica about 35 million years ago and continued drifting northwards.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] When the Last Glacial Period ended, rising sea levels separated the Australian mainland from New Guinea about 8,000 years ago and from Tasmania about 6,000 years ago.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia lies well within the Australian tectonic plate.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The mainland is relatively stable geologically, with no major mountain building, active volcanoes or tectonic faults.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] However, the Australian plate is moving north-northeast at a rate of about 6 to 7 cm a year and is currently in collision with the Eurasian plate and Pacific plate.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The resulting intratectonic stresses lead to relatively high seismic activity for a geologically stable landmass.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There were 18 earthquakes with a moment magnitude of greater than 6 between 1901 and 2017.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Newcastle earthquake of 1989 was Australia's deadliest, killing 13 people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There were active volcanoes on the eastern mainland as recently as 4,600 years ago, and this is reflected in Aboriginal place names and creation stories.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Currently, volcanism occurs in the remote Heard Island and McDonald Islands.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian continental crust was created in three cycles from the oldest Archaean cratons in the west to the younger orogenic formations in the east (built about 541 million to 252 million years ago).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The oldest Australian surface rocks date to the Archaean period.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Some in Western Australia are older than 3.7 billion years and others in South Australia are over 3.1 billion years old.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The oldest zircon crystals on Earth, dating back 4.4 billion years, have been found in Western Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] However, about 80 per cent of Australia is covered by sedimentary rocks and regolith that are less than 250 million years old.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian climate ranges from wet tropical in the northeast and northwest to arid in the centre.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The coastal south is temperate and humid with winter freezing and snow in the southeastern highlands and Tasmania.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The climate is influenced by Australia's position in the "horse latitudes", which tends to bring arid conditions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Overall, the Australian mainland is the driest inhabited continent, with an average annual rainfall of 470 millimetres (19 in).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] About 70% of the country is arid or semi-arid, and about 18% is desert.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The climate is also influenced by various systems such as the El Niño–Southern Oscillation, the Indian Ocean Dipole and the Southern Annular Mode.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has unusual variability in rainfall within years and between years, leading to frequent droughts and flooding.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Cyclones and rain depressions are common in tropical Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The summer monsoon brings significant rainfall to northern Australia and low pressure cells bring winter rainfall in the south.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The hottest regions are in the northwest of the country and the coolest in the southeast.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Bushfire conditions are common in southern Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Climate change from increased greenhouse gas emissions has led to a 1.5 °C rise in Australian temperatures since 1910 and an increase in extreme heat and heavy rainfall events.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There has been a reduction in rainfall from April to October in southern Australia since 1970 and a longer bushfire season since the 1950s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Rainfall has increased in northern Australia since the 1970s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The number of tropical cyclones has fallen since 1982 and alpine snow has decreased since the late 1950s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Sea levels are rising around Australia and the surrounding oceans are becoming more acidic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is one of 17 megadiverse countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Because of its long geographic isolation, much of Australia's biota is unique.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] About 94% of its amphibians, 93% of its reptiles and flowering plants, 69% of its mammals and 46% of its birds are endemic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has a wide range of ecosystems of which 89 regions and 419 subregions are recognised in the Australian bioregion framework.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In January 2025, there were 168,386 named species on the Australian National Species List.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] However, it is estimated that 70% of Australian species have not been discovered and classified and that there may be 600,000 Australian native species.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In general, knowledge of vertebrates and flowering plants is better than for invertebrates and fungi.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is estimated that less that 10% of Australia's fungi and insects have been named.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] About 10% of the world's known plant species are found in Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Many of these have adapted to the arid climate, variable rainfall and nutrient-poor soil.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Deserts and xeric shrubland cover about 70% of the mainland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Acacia, banksia and eucalypts have spread over much of Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Many plants have hard and long-living leaves, and are rich in carbon, poor in nutrients, and well adapted to bushfires.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] About two-thirds of the world's 330 species of marsupials are native to Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australian placental mammals (overwhelmingly bats, rats and mice) also make up almost 47% of the world's land mammal species.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has about 10% of the world's known reptile species.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There are also about 320,500 invertebrate species, of which insects are the largest class, accounting for more than 75% of all animal species.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has over 15,000 known species of fungi, although it is possible that tens of thousands more exist.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's wildlife show many adaptations to their environments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As the leaves of most plants are poor in nutrients, Australia has a high proportion of birds, insects and marsupials, such as the honey possum, that feed on nectar and pollen.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The koala is an exception, specialising in feeding on eucalyptus leaves.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Nutritionally poor flora and variable rainfall also favour animals with lower energy requirements, including snakes, lizards, and hopping marsupials such as the kangaroo and wallaby.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There is, however, evidence of convergent evolution of Australia's marsupials and the placental mammals of other continents living in similar environments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] For example, the extinct thylacine (Tasmanian tiger) had similarities with the placental wolf, marsupial moles with the golden moles of Africa, and hopping mice with the hopping rodents of other arid regions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There were major extinctions of Australia's vertebrates, including its megafauna, about 46 thousand years ago, and there is an ongoing scientific debate over the role of human activity and climate change in these extinctions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The contraction of the range of the Tasmanian tiger and Tasmanian devil to that island about 4,000 to 5,000 years ago is also consistent with changes on the mainland including an increasing human population, the introduction of the dingo, and the greater use of fire and new stone tool technologies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Over the past two centuries, Australia has lost more mammal species than any other continent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Overall, 100 Australian species are listed as extinct or extinct in the wild.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In June 2021, over 1,000 animal and plant species were listed by Australian governments as endangered or critically endangered.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The major threats to endangered species are landscape change, ecosystem disruption, introduced species such as the feral cat and red fox, and climate change.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The federal *Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999* is the legal framework for the protection of threatened species.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The National Reserve System is Australia's network of protected areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As at 30 June 2022, it covered over 22% of Australia's land mass.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] *Australia's Strategy for Nature 2024–2030* is the national biodiversity plan that aims to reverse biodiversity loss in Australia by 2030 and meet the county's obligations under the United Nations Convention on Biological Diversity and other international agreements.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is a constitutional monarchy, a parliamentary democracy and a federation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The country has maintained its mostly unchanged constitution alongside a stable liberal democratic political system since Federation in 1901.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is one of the world's oldest federations, in which power is divided between the federal and state governments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Following elections on 3 May 2025, the prime minister is Anthony Albanese of the Australian Labor Party.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Charles III reigns as King of Australia and is represented in Australia by the governor-general at the federal level and by the governors at the state level, who by section 63 of the Constitution and convention act on the advice of their ministers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Thus, in practice the governor-general acts as a legal figurehead for the actions of the prime minister and the Cabinet.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The governor-general may in some situations exercise reserve powers: powers exercisable in the absence of, or contrary to, ministerial advice.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] When these powers may be exercised is governed by convention and their precise scope is unclear.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The most notable exercise of these powers was the dismissal of the Whitlam government in the constitutional crisis of 1975.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In the Senate (the upper house), there are 76 senators: twelve each from the states and two each from the mainland territories (the Australian Capital Territory and the Northern Territory).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The House of Representatives (the lower house) has 150 members elected from single-member electoral divisions, commonly known as "electorates" or "seats", allocated to states on the basis of population, with each of the current states guaranteed a minimum of five seats.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The lower house has a maximum term of three years, but this is not fixed and governments usually dissolve the house early for an election at some point in the 6 months before the maximum.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Elections for both chambers are generally held simultaneously with senators having overlapping six-year terms except for those from the territories, whose terms are not fixed but are tied to the electoral cycle for the lower house.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Thus, only 40 of the 76 places in the Senate are put to each election unless the cycle is interrupted by a double dissolution.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's electoral system uses preferential voting for the House of Representatives and all state and territory lower house elections (with the exception of Tasmania and the ACT which use the Hare-Clark system).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Senate and most state upper houses use the proportional system which combines preferential voting with proportional representation for each state.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Voting and enrolment is compulsory for all enrolled citizens 18 years and older in every jurisdiction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The party with majority support in the House of Representatives forms the government and its leader becomes prime minister.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The governor-general appoints the prime minister and may dismiss one who has lost the confidence of parliament or acts illegally.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As Australia is a Westminster parliamentary democracy with a powerful and elected upper house, its system has sometimes been called a "Washminster mutation", or semi-parliamentary.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] There are two major political groups that have usually formed government federally: the Australian Labor Party and the Coalition which is a grouping of the Liberal Party and its minor partner, the National Party.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Within Australian political culture, the Labor Party is considered centre-left and the Coalition is considered centre-right.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Independent members and several minor parties have achieved representation in Australian parliaments, mostly in upper houses.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian Greens have been the third largest party by both vote and membership since 2004.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has six states – New South Wales (NSW), Victoria (Vic), Queensland (Qld), Western Australia (WA), South Australia (SA) and Tasmania (Tas) – and two mainland self-governing territories – the Australian Capital Territory (ACT) and the Northern Territory (NT).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The states have the general power to make laws except in the few areas where the constitution grants the Commonwealth (the federal level of government) exclusive powers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Commonwealth can only make laws on topics listed in the constitution but its laws prevail over those of the states to the extent of any inconsistency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Since Federation, the Commonwealth's power relative to the states has significantly increased due to the increasingly wide interpretation given to listed Commonwealth powers – and because of the states' heavy financial reliance on Commonwealth grants.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Each state and major mainland territory has its own parliament – unicameral in the Northern Territory, the ACT and Queensland, and bicameral in the other states.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The lower houses are known as the Legislative Assembly (the House of Assembly in South Australia and Tasmania); the upper houses are known as the Legislative Council.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The head of the government in each state is the premier and in each territory the chief minister.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The King is represented in each state by a governor.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] At the Commonwealth level, the King's representative is the governor-general.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The remote Macquarie Island and Lord Howe Island are part of Tasmania and New South Wales respectively.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is a middle power, whose foreign relations has three core bi-partisan pillars: commitment to the US alliance, engagement with the Indo-Pacific and support for international institutions, rules and co-operation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Through the ANZUS pact and its status as a major non-NATO ally, Australia maintains a close relationship with the US, which encompasses strong defence, security and trade ties.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In the Indo-Pacific, the country seeks to increase its trade ties through the open flow of trade and capital, while managing the rise of Chinese power by supporting the existing rules-based order.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Regionally, the country is a member of the Pacific Islands Forum, the Pacific Community, the ASEAN+6 mechanism and the East Asia Summit.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Internationally, the country is a member of the United Nations (of which it was a founding member), the Commonwealth of Nations, the OECD and the G20.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] This reflects the country's generally strong commitment to multilateralism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has pursued the cause of international trade liberalisation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It led the formation of the Cairns Group and Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation, and is a member of the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) and the World Trade Organization (WTO).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia maintains a deeply integrated relationship with neighbouring New Zealand, with free mobility of citizens between the two countries under the Trans-Tasman Travel Arrangement and free trade under the Closer Economic Relations agreement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The most favourably viewed countries by the Australian people in 2021 include New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Japan, Germany, Taiwan, Thailand, the United States and South Korea.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It also maintains an international aid program under which some 75 countries receive assistance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia ranked fourth in the Center for Global Development's 2021 Commitment to Development Index.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The power over foreign policy is highly concentrated in the prime minister and the national security committee, with major decision such as joining the 2003 invasion of Iraq made without prior Cabinet approval.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Similarly, the Parliament does not play a formal role in foreign policy and the power to declare war lies solely with the executive government.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Department of Foreign Affairs and Trade supports the executive in its policy decisions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The two main institutions involved in the management of Australia's armed forces are the Australian Defence Force (ADF) and the Department of Defence, together known as "Defence".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian Defence Force is the military wing, headed by the chief of the defence force, and contains three branches: the Royal Australian Navy, the Australian Army and the Royal Australian Air Force.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2021, it had 84,865 currently serving personnel (including 60,286 regulars and 24,581 reservists).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Department of Defence is the civilian wing and is headed by the secretary of defence.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] These two leaders collective manage Defence as a diarchy, with shared and joint responsibilities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The titular role of commander-in-chief is held by the governor-general; however, actual command is vested in the chief of the Defence Force.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The executive branch of the Commonwealth government has overall control of the military through the minister of defence, who is subject to the decisions of Cabinet and its National Security Committee.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Major Australian intelligence agencies include the Australian Secret Intelligence Service (foreign intelligence), the Australian Signals Directorate (signals intelligence) and the Australian Security Intelligence Organisation (domestic security).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2022, defence spending was 1.9% of GDP, representing the world's 13th-largest defence budget.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has generally strong protections for civil and political rights, and the country has signed up to a wide range of international rights treaties.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Important documents protecting human rights include the Constitution, the *Racial Discrimination Act 1975*, the *Sex Discrimination Act 1984*, the *Disability Discrimination Act 1992*, and the *Age Discrimination Act 2004*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Same-sex marriage has been legal in the nation since 2017.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Unlike other comparable Western democracies, Australia does not have a single federal charter of rights in the Constitution or under legislation; however, the ACT, Victoria, and Queensland have state-based ones.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] International organisations such as Human Rights Watch and Amnesty International have expressed concerns in areas including asylum-seeker policy, Indigenous deaths in custody, the lack of entrenched rights protection, and laws restricting protesting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia's mixed-market economy is highly developed and rich in natural resources.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It is the world's twelfth largest by nominal terms, and the twenty-third largest by PPP.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As of 2021, Australia has the second-highest amount of wealth per adult, after Luxembourg, and the thirteenth-highest financial assets per capita, as well as one of the highest per capita incomes globally.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It has a labour force of some 13.5 million, with an unemployment rate of 3.5% as of June 2022.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] According to the Australian Council of Social Service, the poverty rate of Australia exceeds 13.6% of the population, encompassing over 3.2 million.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It also estimated that there were 774,000 (17.7%) children under the age of 15 living in relative poverty.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The Australian dollar is the national currency, which is also used by three island states in the Pacific: Kiribati, Nauru, and Tuvalu.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australian government debt, about $963 billion in June 2022, exceeds 45.1% of the country's total GDP, and is the world's eighth-highest.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia had the second-highest level of household debt in the world in 2020, after Switzerland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Its house prices are among the highest in the world, especially in the large urban areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The large service sector accounts for about 71.2% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (25.3%), while its agriculture sector makes up 3.6% of total GDP.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia is the world's 21st-largest exporter and 24th-largest importer.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] China is Australia's largest trading partner, accounting for roughly 40% of the country's exports and 17.6% of its imports.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Other major export markets include Japan, the United States, and South Korea.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia has high levels of competitiveness and economic freedom, and was ranked tenth in the Human Development Index in 2022.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As of 2022, it is ranked twelfth in the Index of Economic Freedom.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] It attracted 9.5 million international tourists in 2019, and was ranked thirteenth among the countries of Asia-Pacific in 2019 for inbound tourism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The 2021 *Travel and Tourism Competitiveness Report* ranked Australia seventh-highest in the world out of 117 countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Its international tourism receipts in 2019 amounted to $45.7 billion.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Total consumption of energy in this period was sourced from coal (28.4%), oil (37.3%), gas (27.4%) and renewables (7%).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] From 2012 to 2022, the energy sourced from renewables has increased 5.7%, while energy sourced from coal has decreased 2.6%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] The use of gas also increased by 1.5% and the use of oil stayed relatively stable with a reduction of only 0.2%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2020, Australia produced 27.7% of its electricity from renewable sources, exceeding the target set by the Commonwealth government in 2009 of 20% renewable energy by 2020.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] A new target of 82% renewable energy by 2030 was set in 2022 and a target for net zero emissions by 2050 was set in 2021.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2019, Australia spent $35.6 billion on research and development, allocating about 1.79% of GDP.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] A 2022 study by the industry lobby group, The Tech Council of Australia, stated that the Australian technology sector combined contributes $167 billion a year to the economy and employs 861,000 people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] In 2022, startup ecosystems in Sydney and Melbourne were valued at $34 billion.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australia ranked 22nd in the Global Innovation Index 2025.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] With only 0.3% of the world's population, Australia contributed over 4% of the world's published research in 2020, making it one of the top 10 research contributors in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] CSIRO, Australia's national science agency, contributes 10% of all research in the country, while the rest is carried out by universities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Australian achievements include the invention of atomic absorption spectroscopy, the essential components of Wi-Fi technology, and the development of the first commercially successful polymer banknote.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] As of 2026, 14 Australian scientists have been awarded the Nobel Prize in physics, chemistry or medicine, and two have been awarded the Fields Medal.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p01] Facilities supporting space exploration include the Square Kilometre Array and Australia Telescope Compact Array radio telescopes, telescopes such as the Siding Spring Observatory, and ground stations such as the Canberra Deep Space Communication Complex.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The population of Australia is estimated to be 27,724,744 as of September 2025.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It is the 54th most populous country in the world and the most populous Oceanian country.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has a population density of 3.4 persons per square kilometre of total land area, which makes it one of the most sparsely populated countries in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The population is heavily concentrated on the east coast, and in particular in the south-eastern region between South East Queensland to the north-east and Adelaide to the south-west.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia is also highly urbanised, with 67% of the population living in the Greater Capital City Statistical Areas (metropolitan areas of the state and mainland territorial capital cities) in 2018.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Metropolitan areas with more than one million inhabitants are Sydney, Melbourne, Brisbane, Perth and Adelaide.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In common with many other developed countries, Australia is experiencing a demographic shift towards an older population, with more retirees and fewer people of working age.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In 2021, the average age of the population was 39 years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has five cities (including their suburbs) that have populations larger than one million people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The majority of Australia's population lives near coastlines.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Between 1788 and the Second World War, the vast majority of settlers and immigrants came from the British Isles (principally England, Ireland and Scotland), although Australia had significant immigration from China and Germany during the 19th century.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Following Federation in 1901, the white Australia policy was strengthened, restricting further migration from these areas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] However, this policy was relaxed following WW2, and in the decades following, Australia received a large wave of immigration from across Europe, with many more immigrants arriving from Southern and Eastern Europe than in previous decades.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Following the end of the White Australia policy in 1973, Australia adopted multiculturalism as policy, culminating in the Racial Discrimination Act 1975.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Subsequently, there has been a large and continuing wave of immigration from across the world, with Asia being the largest source of immigrants in the 21st century.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Today, Australia has the world's eighth-largest immigrant population, with immigrants accounting for 30% of the population, the highest proportion among major Western nations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In 2022–23, 212,789 permanent migrants were admitted to Australia, with a net migration population gain of 518,000 people inclusive of non-permanent residents.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Most entered on skilled visas, however the immigration program also offers visas for family members and refugees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The Australian Bureau of Statistics asks each Australian resident to nominate up to two ancestries each census and the responses are classified into broad ancestry groups.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 3.8% of the Australian population identified as being Indigenous – Aboriginal Australians and Torres Strait Islanders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] English has no legal status in Australia but it is the *de facto* official and national language due to its widespread established use.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australian English is a major variety of the language with a distinctive accent and lexicon, and differs slightly from other varieties of English in grammar and spelling.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] General Australian serves as the standard dialect.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The Australian sign language known as Auslan was used at home by 16,242 people at the time of the 2021 census.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, English was the only language spoken in the home for 72% of the population.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The next most common languages spoken at home were Mandarin (2.7%), Arabic (1.4%), Vietnamese (1.3%), Cantonese (1.2%) and Punjabi (0.9%).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] More than 250 Australian Aboriginal languages are thought to have existed at the time of first European contact.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The National Indigenous Languages Survey (NILS) for 2018–19 found that more than 120 Indigenous language varieties were in use or being revived, although 70 of those in use were endangered.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The 2021 census found that 167 Indigenous languages were spoken at home by 76,978 Indigenous Australians – Yumplatok (Torres Strait Creole), Djambarrpuyngu (a Yolŋu language) and Pitjantjatjara (a Western Desert language) were among the most widely spoken.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] NILS and the Australian Bureau of Statistics use different classifications for Indigenous Australian languages.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has no state religion; section 116 of the Australian Constitution prohibits federal legislation that would establish any religion, impose any religious observance, or prohibit the free exercise of any religion.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] However, the states still retain the power to pass religiously discriminatory laws.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] At the 2021 census, 38.9% of the population identified as having no religion, up from 15.5% in 2001.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The largest religion is Christianity (43.9% of the population).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The largest Christian denominations are the Catholic Church (20% of the population) and the Anglican Church of Australia (9.8%).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Non-British immigration since the Second World War has led to the growth of non-Christian religions, the largest of which are Islam (3.2%), Hinduism (2.7%), Buddhism (2.4%), Sikhism (0.8%), and Judaism (0.4%).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In 2021, just under 8,000 people declared an affiliation with traditional Aboriginal religions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In Australian Aboriginal mythology and the animist framework developed in Aboriginal Australia, the Dreaming is a sacred era in which ancestral totemic spirit beings formed The Creation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The Dreaming established the laws and structures of society and the ceremonies performed to ensure continuity of life and land.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia's life expectancy of 83 years (81 years for males and 85 years for females) is the fifth-highest in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It has the highest rate of skin cancer in the world, while cigarette smoking is the largest preventable cause of death and disease, responsible for 7.8% of the total mortality and disease.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Ranked second in preventable causes is hypertension at 7.6%, with obesity third at 7.5%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia ranked 35th in the world in 2012 for its proportion of obese women and near the top of developed nations for its proportion of obese adults; 63% of its adult population is either overweight or obese.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia spent about 9.91% of its total GDP to health care in 2021.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It introduced a national insurance scheme in 1975.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Following a period in which access to the scheme was restricted, the scheme became universal once more in 1981 under the name of Medicare.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The program is nominally funded by an income tax surcharge known as the Medicare levy, currently at 2%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The states manage hospitals and attached outpatient services, while the Commonwealth funds the Pharmaceutical Benefits Scheme (subsidising the costs of medicines) and general practice.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] School attendance, or registration for home schooling, is compulsory throughout Australia.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Education is primarily the responsibility of the individual states and territories; however, the Commonwealth has significant influence through funding agreements.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Since 2014, a national curriculum developed by the Commonwealth has been implemented by the states and territories.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Attendance rules vary between states, but in general children are required to attend school from the age of about 5 until about 16.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In some states (Western Australia, Northern Territory and New South Wales), children aged 16–17 are required to either attend school or participate in vocational training, such as an apprenticeship.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] According to the 2022 PISA evaluations, Australian 15-year-olds ranked ninth in the OECD for reading and science and tenth for maths.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] However, less than 60% of Australian students achieved the National Proficiency Standard – 51% in maths, 58% in science and 57% in reading.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has an adult literacy rate that was estimated to be 99% in 2003.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] However, a 2011–2012 report for the Australian Bureau of Statistics found that 44% of the population does not have high literary and numeracy competence levels, interpreted by others as suggesting that they do not have the "skills needed for everyday life".
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has 37 government-funded universities and three private universities, as well as a number of other specialist institutions that provide approved courses at the higher education level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The OECD places Australia among the most expensive nations to attend university.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] There is a state-based system of vocational training, known as TAFE, and many trades conduct apprenticeships for training new tradespeople.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] About 58% of Australians aged from 25 to 64 have vocational or tertiary qualifications and the tertiary graduation rate of 49% is the highest among OECD countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] 38% of Australia's population has attained a higher education qualification, which is among the highest percentages in the world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has the highest ratio of international students per head of population in the world by a large margin, with 812,000 international students enrolled in the nation's universities and vocational institutions in 2019.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Accordingly, in 2019, international students represented on average 26.7% of the student bodies of Australian universities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] International education therefore represents one of the country's largest exports and has a pronounced influence on the country's demographics, with a significant proportion of international students remaining in Australia after graduation on various skill and employment visas.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Education is Australia's third-largest export, after iron ore and coal, and contributed more than $28 billion to the economy in the 2016–17 financial year.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Contemporary Australian culture is diverse and reflects the country's Indigenous traditions, British and Irish heritage, and post-1945 history of multicultural immigration.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The culture of the United States has also been influential.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The evolution of Australian culture since British colonisation has given rise to distinctive cultural traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Many Australians identify egalitarianism, mateship, irreverence and a lack of formality as part of their national identity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] These find expression in Australian slang, as well as Australian humour, which is often characterised as dry, irreverent and ironic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] What these values mean, and whether Australians uphold them, has been debated since before Federation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has more than 100,000 Aboriginal rock art sites, and traditional designs, patterns and stories infuse contemporary Indigenous Australian art, "the last great art movement of the 20th century" according to critic Robert Hughes; its exponents include Emily Kame Kngwarreye.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Early colonial artists showed a fascination with the unfamiliar land.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The impressionistic works of Arthur Streeton, Tom Roberts and other members of the 19th-century Heidelberg School – the first "distinctively Australian" movement in Western art – gave expression to nationalist sentiments in the lead-up to Federation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] While the school remained influential into the 1900s, modernists such as Margaret Preston and Clarice Beckett, and, later, Sidney Nolan, explored new artistic trends.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The landscape remained central to the work of Aboriginal watercolourist Albert Namatjira, as well as Fred Williams, Brett Whiteley and other post-war artists whose works, eclectic in style yet uniquely Australian, moved between the figurative and the abstract.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australian literature grew slowly in the decades following European settlement though Indigenous oral traditions, many of which have since been recorded in writing, are much older.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In the 19th century, Henry Lawson and Banjo Paterson captured the experience of the bush using a distinctive Australian vocabulary.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Their works are still popular; Paterson's bush poem "Waltzing Matilda" (1895) is regarded as Australia's unofficial national anthem.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Miles Franklin is the namesake of Australia's most prestigious literary prize, awarded annually to the best novel about Australian life.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Its first recipient, Patrick White, went on to win the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1973.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australian Booker Prize winners include Peter Carey, Thomas Keneally and Richard Flanagan.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australian public intellectuals have also written seminal works in their respective fields, including feminist Germaine Greer and philosopher Peter Singer.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In the performing arts, Aboriginal peoples have traditions of religious and secular song, dance and rhythmic music often performed in corroborees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] At the beginning of the 20th century, Nellie Melba was one of the world's leading opera singers, and later popular music acts such as the Bee Gees, AC/DC, INXS and Kylie Minogue achieved international recognition.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Many of Australia's performing arts companies receive funding through the Australian government's Australia Council.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] There is a symphony orchestra in each state, and a national opera company, Opera Australia, well known for its famous soprano Joan Sutherland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Ballet and dance are represented by The Australian Ballet and various state companies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Each state has a publicly funded theatre company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has two public broadcasters (the Australian Broadcasting Corporation and the multicultural Special Broadcasting Service), three commercial television networks, several pay-TV services, and numerous public, non-profit television and radio stations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Each major city has at least one daily newspaper, and there are two national daily newspapers, *The Australian* and *The Australian Financial Review*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] In 2024, Reporters Without Borders placed Australia 39th on a list of 180 countries ranked by press freedom, behind New Zealand (19th) and the United Kingdom (23rd), but ahead of the United States (55th).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] This relatively low ranking is primarily because of the limited diversity of commercial media ownership in Australia; most print media are under the control of News Corp Australia (59%) and Nine Entertainment (23%).
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Most Indigenous Australian groups subsisted on a diet of native fauna and flora, otherwise called bush tucker.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It has increased in popularity among non-Indigenous Australians since the 1970s, with examples such as lemon myrtle, the macadamia nut and kangaroo meat now widely available.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The first colonists introduced British and Irish cuisine to the continent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] This influence is seen in dishes such as fish and chips, and in the Australian meat pie, which is related to the British steak pie.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Also during the colonial period, Chinese migrants paved the way for a distinctive Australian Chinese cuisine.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Post-war migrants transformed Australian cuisine, bringing with them their culinary traditions and contributing to new fusion dishes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Italians introduced espresso coffee and, along with Greeks, helped develop Australia's café culture, of which the flat white and avocado toast are now considered Australian staples.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Pavlovas, lamingtons, Vegemite and Anzac biscuits are also often called iconic Australian foods.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia is a leading exporter and consumer of wine.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australian wine is produced mainly in the southern, cooler parts of the country.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The nation also ranks highly in beer consumption, with each state and territory hosting numerous breweries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The most popular sports in Australia by adult participation are: swimming, athletics, cycling, soccer, golf, tennis, basketball, surfing, netball and cricket.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia is one of five nations to have participated in every Summer Olympics of the modern era, and has hosted the Games twice: 1956 in Melbourne and 2000 in Sydney.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It is also set to host the 2032 Games in Brisbane.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has also participated in every Commonwealth Games, hosting the event in 1938, 1962, 1982, 2006 and 2018.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The Australian national cricket team competed against England in both the first Test match (1877) and the first One Day International (1971), and against New Zealand in the first Twenty20 International (2004), winning all three games.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] It has also won the men's Cricket World Cup a record six times.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Australia has professional leagues for four football codes, whose relative popularity is divided geographically.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Originating in Melbourne in the 1850s, Australian rules football attracts the most television viewers in all states except New South Wales and Queensland, where rugby league holds sway, followed by rugby union.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] Soccer, while ranked fourth in television viewers and resources, has the highest overall participation rates.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The surf lifesaving movement originated in Australia in the early 20th century, following the relaxation of laws prohibiting daylight bathing on Australian beaches.
[src:chief-executive-officer/australia-p02] The volunteer lifesaver is one of the country's icons.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] The usefulness of this measure in assessing wage levels is debatable, particularly in an economy where low pay is prevalent, due to the tendency for the wages of a minority of high earners to 'skew' the average upwards.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] It has been argued that the median (midpoint) worker's wage is a better indicator in these circumstances; this measure is used in the UK by both the Office for National Statistics and the Scottish Low Pay Unit in examining wage levels.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] Certain UK organisations, usually socialist or left-of-centre political groups, have traditionally had a policy that members should never accept wages higher than the wage of the average working class person whilst being employed by that organisation or in a representative capacity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] This idea is based on the idea that politicians (or trade union officials) are there to serve the people of the country rather than earn themselves a fortune and/or raise their status (also known as careerism).
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] Proponents claim that high wages for politicians are a waste of taxpayers' money and distance the politician from the concerns of the working class.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] Examples of people taking only an average worker's wage are Socialist Party politician Joe Higgins, former MP Dave Nellist in the UK, John Marek, Forward Wales' Welsh Assembly member for Wrexham, and Sinn Féin politicians in Ireland.
[src:chief-executive-officer/average-worker-s-wage] In *The Ragged Trousered Philanthropists*, Robert Tressell notes that the Labour Representation Committee MPs of the day took only an average workers' wage.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In psychology and psychometrics, the **Big Five personality trait model** or **five-factor model** (**FFM**), sometimes called by the mnemonic acronym **OCEAN** or **CANOE**, is a scientific model for measuring and describing human personality traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The five-factor model was developed using empirical research into the language people used to describe themselves, which found patterns and relationships between the words people use to describe themselves.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, because someone described as "hard-working" is more likely to be described as "prepared" and less likely to be described as "messy", all three traits are grouped under conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Using dimensionality reduction techniques, psychologists showed that most (though not all) of the variance in human personality can be explained using only these five factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Today, the five-factor model underlies most contemporary personality research, and has replaced theoretically derived models of personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Research into personality inventories found five broad dimensions could explain most variation in human personality and temperament, with more-detailed analyses typically dividing the traits into more specific subfactors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, extraversion is typically associated with qualities such as gregariousness, assertiveness, excitement-seeking, warmth, activity, and positive emotions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Other models, like HEXACO, supplement the Big 5 traits with additional variables, trading off complexity for model fit.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The Big Five model originated from the lexical hypothesis, which suggests that the most important personality traits are encoded in language.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Raymond Cattell built upon earlier lexical work by reducing thousands of descriptors to 16 personality factors, later clustered into five global traits, which some consider the "original Big Five".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Ernest Tupes and Raymond Christal then analyzed peer ratings of U.S.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Air Force officers and derived five core dimensions: Surgency, Agreeableness, Dependability, Emotional Stability, and Culture—an approach later popularized by Warren Norman.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Digman and colleagues consolidated evidence from previous studies and reaffirmed five major traits, while Paul Costa Jr and Robert R.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] McCrae developed the NEO model, starting with three factors and expanding it into the widely accepted Five Factor Model (FFM).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] These four sets of researchers used somewhat different methods in finding the five traits, making the sets of five factors have varying names and meanings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] However, all have been found to be strongly correlated with their corresponding factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1884, British scientist Sir Francis Galton became the first person known to consider deriving a comprehensive taxonomy of human personality traits by sampling language.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The idea that this may be possible is known as the lexical hypothesis.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] British-American psychologist William McDougall of Duke University proposed five factors in 1929.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1932, these "five distinguishable but inseparable factors" were listed as "intellect, character, temperament, disposition and temper", and have been seen as "anticipating" the adoption of the Big Five model in subsequent years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Swiss psychologist Franziska Baumgarten of the University of Bern implemented the lexical hypothesis, publishing the first psycholexical classification of personality-descriptive terms in 1933.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Using dictionaries and characterology publications, she identified 1093 separate terms in the German language used for the description of personality and mental states.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1936, American psychologists Gordon Allport of Harvard University and Henry Odbert of Dartmouth College implemented the lexical hypothesis using the English language.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They organised for three anonymous people to categorise adjectives from Webster's New International Dictionary and a list of common slang words.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The result was a list of 4504 adjectives they believed were descriptive of observable and relatively permanent traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1943, British-American psychologist Raymond Cattell of Harvard University took Allport and Odbert's list and reduced this to a list of roughly 160 terms by eliminating words with very similar meanings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] To these, he added terms from 22 other psychological categories, and additional "interest" and "abilities" terms.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] From this he used factor analysis to derive 60 "personality clusters or syndromes" and an additional 7 minor clusters.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Cattell then narrowed this down to 35 terms, and later added a 36th factor in the form of an IQ measure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Through factor analysis from 1945 to 1948, he created 11 or 12 factor solutions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1947, German-British psychologist Hans Eysenck of University College London published his book *Dimensions of Personality*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] He posited that the two most important personality dimensions were "Extraversion" and "Neuroticism", a term that he coined.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In the same year, Cattell, (with Maurice Tatsuoka and Herbert Eber), found 4 factors in addition to those they had found before, which they believed consisted of information that could only be provided through self-rating.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] With this understanding, they created and published the sixteen factor 16PF Questionnaire.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1953, John W French of Educational Testing Service published an extensive meta-analysis of personality trait factor studies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1957, Ernest Tupes and Raymond Christal, research psychologists at the Lackland Air Force Base, undertook a personality trait study of US Air Force officers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Each was rated by their peers using Cattell's 35 terms (or in some cases, the 30 most reliable terms).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1958, Tupes and Christal began a US Air Force study by taking 37 personality factors and other data found in Cattell's 1947 paper, Fiske's 1949 paper, and Tupes' 1957 paper.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Through statistical analysis, they derived five factors they labeled "Surgency", "Agreeableness", "Dependability", "Emotional Stability", and "Culture".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In addition to the influence of Cattell and Fiske's work, they strongly noted the influence of French's 1953 study.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Tupes and Christal further tested and explained their 1958 work in a 1961 paper.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Warren Norman of the University of Michigan replicated Tupes and Christal's work in 1963.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] He relabeled "Surgency" as "Extroversion or Surgency", and "Dependability" as "Conscientiousness".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] He also found four subordinate scales for each factor.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Norman's paper was much more read than Tupes and Christal's papers had been.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Norman's later Oregon Research Institute colleague Lewis Goldberg continued this work.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In the 4th edition of the 16PF Questionnaire released in 1968, 5 "global factors" derived from the 16 factors were identified: "Extraversion", "Independence", "Anxiety", "Self-control" and "Tough-mindedness".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] 16PF advocates have since called these "the original big five".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Six factors were found to be present in Finnish people by Jorma Kuusinen of the University of Jyvaskyla in 1969, "Trustworthiness", "Self-confidence", "Rationality", "Uniqueness", "Tolerance", and "Sociability".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1978, Paul Costa and Robert McCrae of the National Institutes of Health published a book chapter describing their Neuroticism-Extraversion-Openness (NEO) model.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The model was based on the three factors in its name.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They used Eysenck's concept of "Extraversion" rather than Carl Jung's.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The authors expanded their explanation of the model in subsequent papers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Also in 1978, British psychologist Peter Saville of Brunel University applied statistical analysis to 16PF results, and determined that the model could be reduced to five factors, "Anxiety", "Extraversion", "Warmth", "Imagination" and "Conscientiousness".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] At a 1980 symposium in Honolulu, Lewis Goldberg, Naomi Takemoto-Chock, Andrew Comrey, and John M.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Digman, reviewed the available personality instruments of the day.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1981, Digman and Takemoto-Chock of the University of Hawaiʻi reanalysed data from Cattell, Tupes, Norman, Fiske and Digman.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They re-affirmed the validity of the five factors, naming them "Friendly Compliance vs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Hostile Non-compliance", "Extraversion vs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Emotional Disorganization", "Will to Achieve" and "Intellect".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They also found weak evidence for the existence of a sixth factor, "Culture".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] 1981 also saw Lewis Goldberg coin the term "Big Five" for the factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Peter Saville and his team included a five-factor "Pentagon" model as part of the Occupational Personality Questionnaires (OPQ) in 1984.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This was the first commercially available Big Five test.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Its factors are "Extroversion", "Vigorous", "Methodical", "Emotional Stability", and "Abstract".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This was closely followed by another commercial test, the NEO PI three-factor personality inventory, published by Costa and McCrae in 1985.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The methodology employed in constructing the NEO instruments has since been subject to critical scrutiny.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Digman of the University of Hawaii further advanced his five-factor model of personality, which Goldberg put at the highest organised level, and was highly cited.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 1992, the NEO PI evolved into the NEO PI-R, adding the factors "Agreeableness" and "Conscientiousness", and becoming a Big Five instrument.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This set the names for the factors that are now most commonly used.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The NEO maintainers called their model the "Five Factor Model" (FFM).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Each NEO personality dimension has six subordinate facets.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Wim Hofstee at the University of Groningen used a lexical hypothesis approach with the Dutch language to develop what became the International Personality Item Pool in the 1990s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Further development in Germany and the United States saw the pool based on three languages.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Its questions and results have been mapped to various Big Five personality typing models.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Kibeom Lee and Michael Ashton released a book describing their HEXACO model in 2004.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] It adds a sixth factor, "Honesty-Humility" to the five (which it calls "Emotionality", "Extraversion", "Agreeableness", "Conscientiousness", and "Openness to Experience").
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Quilty and Jordan Peterson concluded that the 10 aspects of the Big Five may have distinct biological substrates.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This was derived through factor analyses of two data samples with the International Personality Item Pool, followed by cross-correlation with scores derived from 10 genetic factors identified as underlying the shared variance among the Revised NEO Personality Inventory facets.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] By 2009, personality and social psychologists generally agreed that both personal and situational variables are needed to account for human behavior.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] An FFM-associated test was used by Cambridge Analytica, and was part of the "psychographic profiling" controversy during the 2016 US presidential election.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] When factor analysis is applied to personality survey data, semantic associations between aspects of personality and specific terms are often applied to the same person.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, someone described as conscientious is more likely to be described as "always prepared" rather than "messy".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] These associations use terms from common language to describe the human personality, temperament, and psyche.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] These traits are not black and white; each one is a spectrum, with personality varying continuously across each of these dimensions (unlike in the MBTI inventory).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Beneath each proposed global factor, there are a number of correlated and more specific primary factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Openness to experience is a general appreciation for art, emotion, adventure, unusual ideas, imagination, curiosity, and variety of experience.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] People who are open to experience are intellectually curious, open to emotion, sensitive to beauty, and willing to try new things.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They tend to be, when compared to closed people, more creative and more aware of their feelings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They are also more likely to hold unconventional beliefs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Open people can be perceived as unpredictable or lacking focus, and more likely to engage in risky behaviour or drug-taking.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Moreover, individuals with high openness are said to pursue self-actualisation specifically by seeking out intense, euphoric experiences.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Conversely, those with low openness want to be fulfilled by persevering and are characterised as pragmatic and data-driven – sometimes even perceived to be dogmatic and closed-minded.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some disagreement remains about how to interpret and contextualise the openness factor as there is a lack of biological support for this particular trait.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Openness has not shown a significant association with any brain regions as opposed to the other four traits which did when using brain imaging to detect changes in volume associated with each trait.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Conscientiousness is a tendency to be self-disciplined, act dutifully, and strive for achievement against measures or outside expectations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] It is related to people's level of impulse control, regulation, and direction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] High conscientiousness is often perceived as being stubborn and focused.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Low conscientiousness is associated with flexibility and spontaneity, but can also appear as sloppiness and lack of reliability.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] High conscientiousness indicates a preference for planned rather than spontaneous behaviour.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Extraversion is characterised by breadth of activities (as opposed to depth), surgency from external activities/situations, and energy creation from external means.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The trait is marked by pronounced engagement with the external world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Extraverts enjoy interacting with people, and are often perceived as energetic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They tend to be enthusiastic and action-oriented.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They possess high group visibility, like to talk, and assert themselves.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Extraverts may appear more dominant in social settings, as opposed to introverts in that setting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Introverts have lower social engagement and energy levels than extraverts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They tend to seem quiet, low-key, deliberate, and less involved in the social world.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Their lack of social involvement should not be interpreted as shyness or depression, but as greater independence of their social world than extraverts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Introverts need less stimulation and more time alone than extraverts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This does not mean that they are unfriendly or antisocial; rather, they are aloof and reserved in social situations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Generally, people are a combination of extraversion and introversion, with personality psychologist Hans Eysenck suggesting a model by which differences in their brains produce these traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Agreeableness is the general concern for social harmony.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Agreeable individuals value getting along with others.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They are generally considerate, kind, generous, trusting and trustworthy, helpful, and willing to compromise their interests with others.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Agreeable people also have an optimistic view of human nature.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Being agreeable helps us cope with stress.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Disagreeable individuals place self-interest above getting along with others.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They are generally unconcerned with others' well-being and are less likely to extend themselves for other people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Sometimes their skepticism about others' motives causes them to be suspicious, unfriendly, and uncooperative.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Disagreeable people are often competitive or challenging, which can be seen as argumentative or untrustworthy.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Because agreeableness is a social trait, research has shown that one's agreeableness positively correlates with the quality of relationships with one's team members.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Agreeableness also positively predicts transformational leadership skills.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In a study conducted among 169 participants in leadership positions in a variety of professions, individuals were asked to take a personality test and be directly evaluated by supervised subordinates.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Very agreeable leaders were more likely to be considered transformational rather than transactional.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Although the relationship was not strong (*r*=0.32, *β*=0.28, *p*<0.01), it was the strongest of the Big Five traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] However, the same study could not predict leadership effectiveness as evaluated by the leader's direct supervisor.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Conversely, agreeableness has been found to be negatively related to transactional leadership in the military.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A study of Asian military units showed that agreeable people are more likely to be poor transactional leaders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Therefore, with further research, organisations may be able to determine an individual's potential for performance based on their personality traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Neuroticism is the tendency to have strong negative emotions, such as anger, anxiety, or depression.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] It is sometimes called emotional instability, or is reversed and referred to as emotional stability.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Neuroticism is a classic temperament trait that has been studied in temperament research for decades, even before it was adapted by the Five Factor Model.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, in Hans Eysenck's (1967) theory of personality, neuroticism is associated with low tolerance for stress (N+ in the FFM) or a strong dislike of change (O- in the FFM).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Neuroticism in the FFM is similar but not identical to being neurotic in the Freudian sense (i.e., neurosis).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some psychologists prefer to call neuroticism by the term emotional instability to differentiate it from the term neurotic in a career test.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Neurotic people are emotionally volatile, emotionally reactive and vulnerable to stress.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They are more likely to spontaneously experience negative emotions (see sample items below) and their negative emotional reactions tend to stay for longer periods of time, which means they are more often in a bad mood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They are more likely to interpret ordinary situations as threatening.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They can perceive minor frustrations as hopelessly difficult.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For instance, neuroticism is connected to pessimism toward work, to certainty that work hinders personal relationships, and to higher levels of anxiety from the pressures at work.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Furthermore, highly neurotic people may display more skin-conductance reactivity than less neurotic people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] These problems in emotional regulation can make a highly neurotic person think less clearly, make worse decisions, and cope less effectively with stress.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Being disappointed with one's life achievements can make one more neurotic and increase one's chances of falling into clinical depression.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Moreover, neurotic individuals tend to experience more negative life events, but neuroticism also changes in response to positive and negative life experiences.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Also, neurotic people tend to have worse psychological well-being.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] At the other end of the scale, less neurotic individuals are less easily upset and are less emotionally reactive.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] They tend to be calm, emotionally stable, and free from persistent negative feelings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Freedom from negative feelings does not mean that low scorers experience a lot of positive feelings; that is related to extraversion instead.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The most frequently used measures of the Big Five comprise either items that are self-descriptive sentences or, in the case of lexical measures, items that are single adjectives.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Research has suggested that some methodologies in administering personality tests are inadequate in length and provide insufficient detail to truly evaluate personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Usually, longer, more detailed questions will give a more accurate portrayal of personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The five factor structure has been replicated in peer reports.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] However, many of the substantive findings rely on self-reports.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Much of the evidence on the measures of the big five relies on self-report questionnaires, which makes self-report bias and falsification of responses difficult to deal with and account for.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] It has been argued that the Big Five tests do not create an accurate personality profile because the responses given on these tests are not true in all cases and can be falsified.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, questionnaires are answered by potential employees who might choose answers that paint them in the best light.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Thus, the relative-scored measure proved to be less affected by biased responding than the Likert measure of the Big Five.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The five overarching domains of the big five model have been found to contain most known personality traits and are assumed to represent the basic structure behind them all.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Other models, like HEXACO, supplement the big five traits with additional variables.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Factor analysis, the statistical method used to identify the dimensional structure of observed variables, lacks a universally recognized basis for choosing among solutions with different numbers of factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A five factor solution depends on some degree of interpretation by the analyst.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A larger number of factors may underlie these five factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This has led to disputes about the "true" number of factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Big Five proponents have responded that although other solutions may be viable in a single data set, only the five-factor structure consistently replicates across different studies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Block argues that the use of factor analysis as the exclusive paradigm for conceptualizing personality is too limited.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some research suggests that the Big Five should not be conceived of as dichotomies (such as extraversion vs. introversion) but as continua.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Each individual has the capacity to move along each dimension as circumstances (social or temporal) change.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The aspects are labelled as follows: Volatility and Withdrawal for Neuroticism; Enthusiasm and Assertiveness for Extraversion; Intellect and Openness for Openness to Experience; Industriousness and Orderliness for Conscientiousness; and Compassion and Politeness for Agreeableness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In many studies, the five factors are not fully orthogonal to one another; that is, the five factors are not independent.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Orthogonality is viewed as desirable by some researchers because it minimizes redundancy between the dimensions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] This is particularly important when the goal of a study is to provide a comprehensive description of personality with as few variables as possible.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Cheung, van de Vijver, and Leong (2011) suggest that the Openness factor is particularly unsupported in Asian countries and that a different fifth factor is identified.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Attempts to replicate the Big Five have succeeded in some countries but not in others.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some research suggests, for instance, that Hungarians do not have a single agreeableness factor.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Other researchers have found evidence for agreeableness but not for other factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] There may be debate as to what counts as personality and what does not and the nature of the questions in the survey greatly influence outcome.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Multiple particularly broad question databases have failed to produce the Big Five as the top five traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The structure, manifestations, and development of the Big Five in childhood and adolescence have been studied using a variety of methods, including parent- and teacher-ratings, preadolescent and adolescent self- and peer-ratings, and observations of parent-child interactions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Results from these studies support the relative stability of personality traits across the human lifespan, at least from preschool age through adulthood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] More specifically, research suggests that four of the Big Five – namely Extraversion, Neuroticism, Conscientiousness, and Agreeableness – reliably describe personality differences in childhood, adolescence, and adulthood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] However, some evidence suggests that Openness may not be a fundamental, stable part of childhood personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Although some researchers have found that Openness in children and adolescents relates to attributes such as creativity, curiosity, imagination, and intellect, many researchers have failed to find distinct individual differences in Openness in childhood and early adolescence.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Potentially, Openness may (a) manifest in unique, currently unknown ways in childhood or (b) may only manifest as children develop socially and cognitively.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Other studies have found evidence for all of the Big Five traits in childhood and adolescence as well as two other child-specific traits: Irritability and Activity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some researchers have proposed the youth personality trait is best described by six trait dimensions: neuroticism, extraversion, openness to experience, agreeableness, conscientiousness, and activity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Despite some preliminary evidence for this "Little Six" model, research in this area has been delayed by a lack of available measures.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Some cross-cultural research has shown some patterns of gender differences on responses to the NEO-PI-R and the Big Five Inventory.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] For example, women consistently report higher Neuroticism, Agreeableness, warmth (an extraversion facet) and openness to feelings, and men often report higher assertiveness (a facet of extraversion) and openness to ideas as assessed by the NEO-PI-R.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A study of gender differences in 55 nations using the Big Five Inventory found that women tended to be somewhat higher than men in neuroticism, extraversion, agreeableness, and conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The difference in neuroticism was the most prominent and consistent, with significant differences found in 49 of the 55 nations surveyed.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Gender differences in personality traits are largest in prosperous, healthy, and more gender-egalitarian nations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The explanation for this, as stated by the researchers of a 2001 paper, is that actions by women in individualistic, egalitarian countries are more likely to be attributed to their personality, rather than being attributed to ascribed gender roles within collectivist, traditional countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Measured differences in the magnitude of sex differences between more or less developed world regions were caused by the changes in the measured personalities of men, not women, in these respective regions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] That is, men in highly developed world regions were less neurotic, less extraverted, less conscientious and less agreeable compared to men in less developed world regions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Women, on the other hand tended not to differ in personality traits across regions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Frank Sulloway argues that firstborns are more conscientious, more socially dominant, less agreeable, and less open to new ideas compared to siblings that were born later.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Large-scale studies using random samples and self-report personality tests, however, have found milder effects than Sulloway claimed, or no significant effects of birth order on personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Parental socioeconomic status and participant gender had much larger correlations with personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] In 2002, the Journal of Psychology posted a Big Five Personality Trait Difference; where researchers explored the relationship between the five-factor model and the Universal-Diverse Orientation (UDO) in counselor trainees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] UDO is known as one social attitude that produces a strong awareness and/or acceptance towards the similarities and differences among individuals.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] (Miville, M., Romas, J., Johnson, J., and Lon, R.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] 2002) The study found that the counselor trainees that are more open to the idea of creative expression (a facet of Openness to Experience, Openness to Aesthetics) among individuals are more likely to work with a diverse group of clients, and feel comfortable in their role.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A 1996 behavioural genetics study of twins suggested that heritability (the degree of *variation* in a trait within a population that is due to genetic variation in that population) and environmental factors both influence all five factors to the same degree.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Among four twin studies examined in 2003, the mean percentage for heritability was calculated for each personality and it was concluded that heritability influenced the five factors broadly.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The self-report measures were as follows: openness to experience was estimated to have a 57% genetic influence, extraversion 54%, conscientiousness 49%, neuroticism 48%, and agreeableness 42%.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] The Big Five personality traits have been assessed in some non-human species but methodology is debatable.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Neuroticism and openness factors were found in an original zoo sample, but were not replicated in a new zoo sample or in other settings (perhaps reflecting the design of the assessment scale).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A study review found that markers for the three dimensions extraversion, neuroticism, and agreeableness were found most consistently across different species, followed by openness; only chimpanzees showed markers for conscientious behavior.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] A study completed in 2020 concluded that dolphins have some similar personality traits to humans.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p01] Both are large brained intelligent animals but have evolved separately for millions of years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The Big Five model has become a dominant framework in contemporary personality psychology.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Its wide acceptance stems from strong empirical support and its practical utility in both research and applied settings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However, its applicability is not universal, and several methodological and conceptual criticisms limit its effectiveness in certain contexts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Some diseases cause changes in personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For example, although gradual memory impairment is the hallmark feature of Alzheimer's disease, a systematic review of personality changes in Alzheimer's disease by Robins Wahlin and Byrne, published in 2011, found systematic and consistent trait changes mapped to the Big Five.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The largest change observed was a decrease in conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The next most significant changes were an increase in Neuroticism and decrease in Extraversion, but Openness and Agreeableness were also decreased.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These changes in personality could assist with early diagnosis.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] A study published in 2023 found that the Big Five personality traits may also influence the quality of life experienced by people with Alzheimer's disease and other dementias, post diagnosis.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In this study people with dementia with lower levels of Neuroticism self-reported higher quality of life than those with higher levels of Neuroticism while those with higher levels of the other four traits self-reported higher quality of life than those with lower levels of these traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This suggests that as well as assisting with early diagnosis, the Big Five personality traits could help identify people with dementia potentially more vulnerable to adverse outcomes and inform personalized care planning and interventions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] As of 2002, there were over fifty published studies relating the FFM to personality disorders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Since that time, quite a number of additional studies have expanded on this research base and provided further empirical support for understanding the DSM personality disorders in terms of the FFM domains.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This proposal underscores its growing acceptance and utility in clinical psychology for understanding and assessing personality pathology.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In her review of the personality disorder literature published in 2007, Lee Anna Clark asserted that "the five-factor model of personality is widely accepted as representing the higher-order structure of both normal and abnormal personality traits".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However, other researchers disagree that this model is widely accepted (see the section Critique below) and suggest that it simply replicates early temperament research.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Noticeably, FFM publications never compare their findings to temperament models even though temperament and mental disorders (especially personality disorders) are thought to be based on the same neurotransmitter imbalances, just to varying degrees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The five-factor model was claimed to significantly predict all ten personality disorder symptoms and outperform the Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (MMPI) in the prediction of borderline, avoidant, and dependent personality disorder symptoms.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However, most predictions related to an increase in Neuroticism and a decrease in Agreeableness, and therefore did not differentiate between the disorders very well.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The Five Factor personality profiles of users of different drugs may be different.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For example, the typical profile for heroin users is ${\rm {N}}\Uparrow ,{\rm {O}}\Uparrow ,{\rm {A}}\Downarrow ,{\rm {C}}\Downarrow$ , whereas for ecstasy users the high level of N is not expected but E is higher: ${\rm {E}}\Uparrow ,{\rm {O}}\Uparrow ,{\rm {A}}\Downarrow ,{\rm {C}}\Downarrow$ .
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These common mental disorders (CMDs) have been empirically linked to the Big Five personality traits, neuroticism in particular.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Numerous studies have found that having high scores of neuroticism significantly increases one's risk for developing a common mental disorder.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This finding parallels research on physical health, which has established that conscientiousness is the strongest personality predictor of reduced mortality, and is highly negatively correlated with making poor health choices.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In regards to the other personality domains, the meta-analysis found that all common mental disorders examined were defined by high neuroticism, most exhibited low extraversion, only SUD was linked to agreeableness (negatively), and no disorders were associated with Openness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] A meta-analysis of 59 longitudinal studies showed that high neuroticism predicted the development of anxiety, depression, substance abuse, psychosis, schizophrenia, and non-specific mental distress, also after adjustment for baseline symptoms and psychiatric history.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Five major models have been posed to explain the nature of the relationship between personality and mental illness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] There is currently no single "best model", as each of them has received at least some empirical support.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These models are not mutually exclusive – more than one may be operating for a particular individual and various mental disorders may be explained by different models.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The predictive effects of the Big Five personality traits relate mostly to social functioning and rules-driven behavior and are not very specific for prediction of particular aspects of behavior.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For example, it was noted by all temperament researchers that high neuroticism precedes the development of all common mental disorders and is not associated with personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Further evidence is required to fully uncover the nature and differences between personality traits, temperament and life outcomes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Social and contextual parameters also play a role in outcomes and the interaction between the two is not yet fully understood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The dimensional trait models of the ICD‐11 and DSM‐5 Section III were explicitly made consistent with the FFM.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The FFM is also the personality and temperament foundation for the Hierarchical Taxonomy of Psychopathology.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Personality can sometimes be flexible and measuring the big five personality for individuals as they enter certain stages of life may predict their educational identity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Recent studies have suggested the likelihood of an individual's personality affecting their educational identity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] It is also believed that the Big Five traits are predictors of future performance outcomes to varying degrees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Specific facets of the Big Five traits are also thought to be indicators of success in the workplace, and each individual facet can give a more precise indication as to the nature of a person.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Different traits' facets are needed for different occupations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Various facets of the Big Five traits can predict the success of people in different environments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The estimated levels of an individual's success in jobs that require public speaking versus one-on-one interactions will differ according to whether that person has particular traits' facets.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Personality plays an important role in academic achievement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] A study of Israeli high-school students found that those in the gifted program systematically scored higher on openness and lower on neuroticism than those not in the gifted program.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] While not a measure of the Big Five, gifted students also reported less state anxiety than students not in the gifted program.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Another study found that GPA and exam performance are both predicted by conscientiousness while neuroticism is negatively related to academic success.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In a study, conscientiousness predicted success in the transition from secondary school to vocational education and training (VET).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Extraversion predicted the final VET grade and obtaining a VET position; agreeableness was linked to a higher risk of dropout.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Effect sizes were small but comparable to established predictors such as cognitive ability and parental socioeconomic status.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Learning styles have been described as "enduring ways of thinking and processing information".
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In 2008, the Association for Psychological Science (APS) commissioned a report that concludes that no significant evidence exists that learning-style assessments should be included in the education system.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Thus it is premature, at best, to conclude that the evidence links the Big Five to "learning styles", or "learning styles" to learning itself.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However, the APS report also suggested that all existing learning styles have not been exhausted and that there could exist learning styles worthy of being included in educational practices.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] There are studies that conclude that personality and thinking styles may be intertwined in ways that link thinking styles to the Big Five personality traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] There is no general consensus on the number or specifications of particular learning styles, but there have been many different proposals.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] When all four facets are implicated within the classroom, they will each likely improve academic achievement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Moreover, extraversion and openness were proportional to elaborative processing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The Big Five personality traits accounted for 14% of the variance in GPA, suggesting that personality traits make some contributions to academic performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Furthermore, reflective learning styles (synthesis-analysis and elaborative processing) were able to mediate the relationship between openness and GPA.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These results indicate that intellectual curiosity significantly enhances academic performance if students combine their scholarly interest with thoughtful information processing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] By identifying learning strategies in individuals, learning and academic achievement can be improved, and a deeper understanding of information processing can be gained.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This model asserts that students develop either agentic/shallow processing or reflective/deep processing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Deep processors are more often found to be more conscientious, intellectually open, and extraverted than shallow processors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Deep processing is associated with appropriate study methods (methodical study) and a stronger ability to analyze information (synthesis analysis), whereas shallow processors prefer structured fact retention learning styles and are better suited for elaborative processing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Openness has been linked to learning styles that often lead to academic success and higher grades like synthesis analysis and methodical study.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Because conscientiousness and openness have been shown to predict all four learning styles, it suggests that individuals who possess characteristics like discipline, determination, and curiosity are more likely to engage in all of the above learning styles.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] According to the research carried out by Komarraju, Karau, Schmeck & Avdic (2011), conscientiousness and agreeableness are positively related with all four learning styles, whereas neuroticism was negatively related with those four.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Furthermore, extraversion and openness were only positively related to elaborative processing, and openness itself correlated with higher academic achievement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In addition, a previous study by psychologist Mikael Jensen has shown relationships between the Big Five personality traits, learning, and academic achievement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] According to Jensen, all personality traits, except neuroticism, are associated with learning goals and motivation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Openness and conscientiousness influence individuals to learn to a high degree unrecognized, while extraversion and agreeableness have similar effects.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Conscientiousness and neuroticism also influence individuals to perform well in front of others for a sense of credit and reward, while agreeableness forces individuals to avoid this strategy of learning.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Jensen's study concludes that individuals who score high on the agreeableness trait will likely learn just to perform well in front of others.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Besides openness, all Big Five personality traits helped predict the educational identity of students.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Based on these findings, scientists are beginning to see that the Big Five traits might have a large influence of on academic motivation that leads to predicting a student's academic performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Some authors suggested that Big Five personality traits combined with learning styles can help predict some variations in the academic performance and the academic motivation of an individual which can then influence their academic achievements.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This may be seen because individual differences in personality represent stable approaches to information processing.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For instance, conscientiousness has consistently emerged as a stable predictor of success in exam performance, largely because conscientious students experience fewer study delays.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Conscientiousness shows a positive association with the four learning styles because students with high levels of conscientiousness develop focused learning strategies and appear to be more disciplined and achievement-oriented.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] In addition, it was found that self-discipline, extraversion, and adaptability personality traits are generally in a positive relationship with academic achievement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The most important personality trait that has a negative relationship with academic achievement has emerged as neuroticism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] The results generally show that individuals who are organized, planned, determined, who are oriented to new ideas and independent thinking have increased success in distance education environments.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] On the other hand, it can be said that individuals with anxiety and stress tendencies generally have lower academic success.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Researchers have long suggested that work is more likely to be fulfilling to the individual and beneficial to society when there is alignment between the person and their occupation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For instance, software programmers and scientists often rank high on Openness to experience and tend to be intellectually curious, think in symbols and abstractions, and find repetition boring.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Psychologists and sociologists rank higher on Agreeableness and Openness than economists and jurists.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Research has demonstrated that the big five personality traits correlate with important work outcomes such as job performance, training proficiency, and turnover.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] For example, an early meta-analysis found an estimated population correlation of 0.26 between conscientiousness and supervisory ratings of job performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These results are consistent with research suggesting that personality traits predict a broad range of important life outcomes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However, these criterion-related validity results have been criticized, in part because of the apparently weak correlations: "The problem with personality tests is ... that the validity of personality measures as predictors of job performance is often disappointingly low.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] One way to explain this controversy is that there is little doubt that personality predicts a broad array of important outcomes but it is also clear that other selection methods have higher validity as compared to personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Research has suggested that individuals who are considered leaders typically exhibit lower amounts of neurotic traits, maintain higher levels of openness, balanced levels of conscientiousness, and balanced levels of extraversion.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Further studies have linked professional burnout to neuroticism, and extraversion to enduring positive work experience.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Studies have linked national innovation, leadership, and ideation to openness to experience and conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Occupational self-efficacy has also been shown to be positively correlated with conscientiousness and negatively correlated with neuroticism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Some research has also suggested that the conscientiousness of a supervisor is positively associated with an employee's perception of abusive supervision.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Others have suggested that low agreeableness and high neuroticism are traits more related to abusive supervision.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Openness is positively related to proactivity at the individual and the organizational levels and is negatively related to team and organizational proficiency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] These effects were found to be completely independent of one another.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] This is also counter-conscientious and has a negative correlation to Conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Agreeableness is negatively related to individual task proactivity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Typically this is associated with lower career success and being less able to cope with conflict.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] However there are benefits to the Agreeableness personality trait including higher subjective well-being; more positive interpersonal interactions and helping behavior; lower conflict; lower deviance and turnover.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Furthermore, attributes related to Agreeableness are important for workforce readiness for a variety of occupations and performance criteria.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p02] Research has suggested that those who are high in agreeableness are not as successful in accumulating income.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Extraversion results in greater leadership emergence and effectiveness; as well as higher job and life satisfaction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However extraversion can lead to more impulsive behaviors, more accidents and lower performance in certain jobs.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Conscientiousness is highly predictive of job performance in general, and is positively related to all forms of work role performance, including job performance and job satisfaction, greater leadership effectiveness, lower turnover and deviant behaviors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However this personality trait is associated with reduced adaptability, lower learning in initial stages of skill acquisition and more interpersonally abrasiveness, when also low in agreeableness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] It is also not the case that more or extreme conscientiousness is always necessarily better as there does appear to be a link between conscientiousness and obsessive-compulsive personality disorder (OCPD).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Selecting employees for a moderate level of conscientiousness may actually provide the best occupational outcome.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Neuroticism is negatively related to all forms of work role performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] This increases the chance of engaging in risky behaviors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Two theories have been integrated in an attempt to account for these differences in work role performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Trait activation theory posits that within a person trait levels predict future behavior, that trait levels differ between people, and that work-related cues activate traits which leads to work relevant behaviors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Role theory suggests that role senders provide cues to elicit desired behaviors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In this context, role senders provide workers with cues for expected behaviors, which in turn activates personality traits and work relevant behaviors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In essence, expectations of the role sender lead to different behavioral outcomes depending on the trait levels of individual workers, and because people differ in trait levels, responses to these cues will not be universal.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] As of 2020, remote work has become more and more prevalent as brought on by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However, research has shown that the Big Five personality traits still influence remote work.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Gavoille and Hazans have found that conscientiousness (β=0.06) and openness to experience are both positively correlated with willingness to work and worker productivity within a remote setting, with openness to experience being less significant (β=0.021).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] This is then contrasted with extraversion (β=-0.038), which negatively correlates with Willingness to work and openness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Another conclusion that was found is that gender did not play a role in the difference between conscientiousness and extraversion, and willingness to work from home.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Similarly, Wright investigated the influence of Big Five on the soft skills in the remote workplace, such as effort and cooperation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] She delineated soft skills into two different groups, Task Performance and Contextual Performance, with each having three subgroups.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Task Performance was more aligned with specific job responsibilities and handling cognitive tasks associated with their job, and the three subgroups were Job Knowledge, Organizational Skills, and Efficiency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Contextual Performance is concerned with non-job core requirements, such as perceived effort and job cooperation, with the subgroups being Persistent Effort, Cooperation, and Organizational Conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Wright found that Persistent Effort is positively correlated with Openness(t=2.4, P=.014) and Conscientiousness (T=3.1, P=.002), and negatively correlated with Neuroticism (T=-3.2, P=.001).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] On another tack, scientists wanted to discover if the Big Five has any effect on remote worker burnout, and the effect that different Big Five traits have on worker health and engagement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However, Olsen found that conscientiousness, coupled with an increase in remote work days, can lead to a decrease in general health, contrary to all of the benefits it has listed above.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Similarly, Para et al. found that individuals with higher Neuroticism (β=.138, p<.05) also tend to have higher Remote Work Exhaustion (RWE).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] They also found that conscientiousness(β=-.336, p<.001) and agreeableness (β=-.267, p<.001) were negatively correlated with RWE, meaning that they were more resilient against RWE over large spans of remote work days.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Research into the Big Five has been pursued in a variety of languages and cultures, such as German, Chinese, and South Asian.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, Thompson has claimed to find the Big Five structure across several cultures using an international English language scale.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Studies of the Revised NEO Personality Inventory, which has been translated into more than forty languages and dialects, have found an approximation to the five-factor structure in more than thirty cultures examined.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] These findings do not rule out additional personality traits specific to individual cultures, and the factors may not be equally important in every culture.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, Openness to Experience might be less important in traditional cultures.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Individual differences in personality traits are widely understood to be conditioned by cultural context.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Measures of the Big Five constructs appear to show some consistency in interviews, self-descriptions and observations, and this static five-factor structure seems to be found across a wide range of participants of different ages and cultures.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Surveys in studies are often online surveys of college students (compare WEIRD bias).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Results do not always replicate when run on other populations or in other languages.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Different surveys do not always measure the same 5 factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] (2008) found that European-American men scored higher than Asian-American men on extroversion, conscientiousness, and openness, while Asian-American men scored higher than European-American men on neuroticism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Benet-Martínez and Karakitapoglu-Aygün (2003) arrived at similar results.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Recent work has found relationships between Geert Hofstede's cultural factors, Individualism, Power Distance, Masculinity, and Uncertainty Avoidance, with the average Big Five scores in a country.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For instance, the degree to which a country values individualism correlates with its average extraversion, whereas people living in cultures which are accepting of large inequalities in their power structures tend to score somewhat higher on conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] A 2017 study has found that countries' average personality trait levels are correlated with their political systems.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Countries with higher average trait Openness tended to have more democratic institutions, an association that held even after factoring out other relevant influences such as economic development.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] One limitation highlighted by cross-cultural research is that studies supporting the universality of the Five-Factor Model are often from 2002 or older, which can influence current results.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Methodological concerns may also arise from the reliance on Western-Developed instruments in some cross-cultural studies, affecting the validity of findings in diverse cultural contexts.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The Big Five Personality Model also has applications in the study of political psychology.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Studies have been finding links between the big five personality traits and political identification.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] It has been found by several studies in the West that individuals who score high in Conscientiousness are more likely to possess a right-wing political identification.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] On the opposite end of the spectrum, a strong correlation was identified between high scores in Openness to Experience and a left-leaning ideology.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] While the traits of agreeableness, extraversion, and neuroticism have not been consistently linked to either conservative or liberal ideology, with studies producing mixed results, such traits are promising when analyzing the strength of an individual's party identification.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However, correlations between the Big Five and political beliefs, while present, tend to be small, with one study finding correlations ranged from 0.14 to 0.24.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Though the effect sizes are small: Of the Big Five personality traits high Agreeableness, Conscientiousness and Extraversion relate to general religiosity, while Openness relate negatively to religious fundamentalism and positively to spirituality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] High Neuroticism may be related to extrinsic religiosity, whereas intrinsic religiosity and spirituality reflect Emotional Stability.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Schwartz analyzed 700 million words, phrases, and topic instances collected from the Facebook messages of 75,000 volunteers, who also took standard personality tests, and found striking variations in language with personality, gender, and age.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Some consider the big five model as inappropriate for studying early childhood, as language is not yet developed.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] There are debates between temperament researchers and personality researchers as to whether or not biologically based differences define a concept of temperament or a part of personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The presence of such differences in pre-cultural individuals (such as animals or young infants) suggests that they belong to temperament since personality is a socio-cultural concept.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For this reason developmental psychologists generally interpret individual differences in children as an expression of temperament rather than personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Some researchers argue that temperaments and personality traits are age-specific demonstrations of virtually the same internal qualities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Some believe that early childhood temperaments may become adolescent and adult personality traits as individuals' basic genetic characteristics interact with their changing environments to various degrees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Researchers of adult temperament point out that, similarly to sex, age, and mental illness, temperament is based on biochemical systems whereas personality is a product of socialisation of an individual possessing these four types of features.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Temperament interacts with socio-cultural factors, but, similar to sex and age, still cannot be controlled or easily changed by these factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Temperament researchers point out that the lack of attention to surviving temperament research by the creators of the Big Five model led to an overlap between its dimensions and dimensions described in multiple temperament models much earlier.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, neuroticism reflects the traditional temperament dimension of emotionality studied by Jerome Kagan's group since the 1960s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Extraversion was first introduced by Jung in the 1920s.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In Big Five studies, extraversion has been associated with surgency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Children with high Extraversion are energetic, talkative, social, and dominant with children and adults, whereas children with low extraversion tend to be quiet, calm, inhibited, and submissive to other children and adults.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Individual differences in extraversion first manifest in infancy as varying levels of positive emotionality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] These differences in turn predict social and physical activity during later childhood and may represent, or be associated with, the behavioral activation system.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In children, Extraversion/Positive Emotionality includes four sub-traits: three of these (*activity*, *sociability*, and *shyness*) are similar to the previously described traits of temperament; the other is *dominance*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Research on the Big Five, and personality in general, has focused primarily on individual differences in adulthood, rather than in childhood and adolescence, and often include temperament traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Recently, there has been growing recognition of the need to study child and adolescent personality trait development in order to understand how traits develop and change throughout the lifespan.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Recent studies have begun to explore the developmental origins and trajectories of the Big Five among children and adolescents, especially those that relate to temperament.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Many researchers have sought to distinguish between personality and temperament.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Temperament often refers to early behavioral and affective characteristics that are thought to be driven primarily by genes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Models of temperament often include four trait dimensions: surgency/sociability, negative emotionality, persistence/effortful control, and activity level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Some of these differences in temperament are evident at, if not before, birth.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, both parents and researchers recognize that some newborn infants are peaceful and easily soothed while others are comparatively fussy and hard to calm.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Unlike temperament, however, many researchers view the development of personality as gradually occurring throughout childhood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Contrary to some researchers who question whether children have stable personality traits, Big Five or otherwise, most researchers contend that there are significant psychological differences between children that are associated with relatively stable, distinct, and salient behavior patterns.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Findings from studies indicate that, consistent with adult personality trends, youth personality becomes increasingly more stable in terms of rank-order throughout childhood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The disruption hypothesis, which proposes that biological, social, and psychological changes experienced during youth result in temporary dips in maturity, has been proposed to explain these findings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] It is shown that the personality stabilizes for working-age individuals within about four years after starting working.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] There is also little evidence that adverse life events can have any significant impact on the personality of individuals.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] More recent research and meta-analyses of previous studies, however, indicate that change occurs in all five traits at various points in the lifespan.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The new research shows evidence for a maturation effect.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] On average, levels of agreeableness and conscientiousness typically increase with time, whereas extraversion, neuroticism, and openness tend to decrease.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Research has also demonstrated that changes in Big Five personality traits depend on the individual's current stage of development.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, levels of agreeableness and conscientiousness demonstrate a negative trend during childhood and early adolescence before trending upwards during late adolescence and into adulthood.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In addition to these group effects, there are individual differences: different people demonstrate unique patterns of change at all stages of life.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Previous research has found evidence that most adults become more agreeable and conscientious and less neurotic as they age.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] This has been referred to as the maturation effect.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Many researchers have sought to investigate how trends in adult personality development compare to trends in youth personality development.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Two main population-level indices have been important in this area of research: rank-order consistency and mean-level consistency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Rank-order consistency indicates the relative placement of individuals within a group.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Mean-level consistency indicates whether groups increase or decrease on certain traits throughout the lifetime.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Research regarding personality with growing age has suggested that as individuals enter their elder years (79–86), those with lower IQ see a raise in extraversion, but a decline in conscientiousness and physical well-being.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Out of the Big Five personality traits, they found neuroticism most related to worse subjective health outcomes and optimistic control to better subjective health outcomes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] When relating to objective health conditions, connections drawn were presented weak, except that neuroticism significantly predicted chronic illness, whereas optimistic control was more closely related to physical injuries caused by accident.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Being highly conscientious may add as much as five years to one's life.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The Big Five personality traits also predict positive health outcomes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In an elderly Japanese sample, conscientiousness, extraversion, and openness were related to lower risk of mortality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Higher conscientiousness is associated with lower obesity risk.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In already obese individuals, higher conscientiousness is associated with a higher likelihood of becoming non-obese over a five-year period.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Studies conducted on college students have concluded that hope, which is linked to agreeableness, conscientiousness, neuroticism, and openness, has a positive effect on psychological well-being.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Individuals high in neurotic tendencies are less likely to display hopeful tendencies and are negatively associated with well-being.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Various researchers have explored the association of Big Five and romantic relationships in terms of relationship satisfaction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] A meta-analysis showed that there was a higher level of marital satisfaction if their spouse showed lower levels in neuroticism (.22), but higher levels in agreeableness (.15) and conscientiousness(.12).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] There was only a weak correlation, but it was the same level of satisfaction for both genders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Much like the previous meta-analysis, a study on self-reported big five traits showed that those with higher levels of agreeableness, emotional stability, conscientiousness, and extraversion had higher levels of marital satisfaction(.20).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] That same study found that there was little to no difference in marital satisfaction if the two partners had similar or different levels of trait personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] O'Brien and colleagues examined the association of Big Five and romantic relationships by investigating participants' commitment levels.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The three levels of commitment are affective commitment (emotional attachment), continuance commitment (financial considerations), and normative commitment (the ethical and moral responsibilities).
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The commitment levels were based on the taxonomy of organizational commitment and the conceptual model of marital commitment of Johnson and Johnson et al.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] 122 Individuals currently in a committed relationship responded to a 50-item personality questionnaire from the International Personality Item Pool (IPIP, 2006), and a questionnaire on commitment modified from Allen.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The key findings showed that participants high in Extraversion reported high levels of affective commitment; participants high on Extraversion were higher on Openness to Experience and affective commitment.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Conscientiousness demonstrated a negative relationship with continuance commitment.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] While Extraversion and Agreeableness exhibited a positive correlation with each other, no significant relationships were found between Agreeableness and any of the commitment measures.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The findings indicated gender differences in that women with lower levels of Openness to Experience were often paired with partners who scored higher in Extraversion.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Men who exhibited strong affective commitment were more likely to be in relationships with women high in Conscientiousness.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Additionally, women whose partners showed high affective commitment tended to be higher in both Conscientiousness and Emotional Stability.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Asselmann and Sprecht examined the association of Big Five (BFI-S) and romantic relationships through major life events across years in 2005, 2009, 2013, and 2017 with a sample of 49,932 participants in Germany.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Those major life events are (1) moving in with a partner, (2) getting married, (3) getting separated, and (4) getting divorced.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Researchers also examined whether the Big Five personality traits play a significant role in romantic relationships.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Along the spectrum of a person's life satisfaction, marital satisfaction (one of romantic relationships) is shown to be stronger than job satisfaction, health satisfaction, and social satisfaction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The key findings from Asselmann and Sprecht showed that more extraverted individuals were more likely to move in with a partner.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Less agreeable and less emotionally stable women were more likely to move in with a partner.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Men were more extraverted in the years before moving in and became gradually more open and more conscientious after moving in.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Less agreeable men were more likely to get married.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Individuals who got married became less open in the first three years after the marriage.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Women became more extraverted after being separated.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Men with lower emotional stability and women who were both less emotionally stable and more extraverted were more prone to experiencing relationship breakups.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Individuals who got divorced were less agreeable in the years before the divorce.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Personality may change after specific events.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For example, both men and women who experienced separation or divorce became less emotionally stable in the following years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The results implicated that total agreeableness was not a guarantee for long-lasting romantic relationships, as less agreeable individuals were more likely to experience both positive and negative major romantic events.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Getting into a long-term romantic relationship can kick-start personality development in young adults ages 20–30 as they are faced with new social situations and expectations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] For instance, high levels of trait neuroticism at the beginning of relationships can be seen decreasing over 8 years once the relationship has begun, as well as other Big Five personality traits, such as Conscientiousness and Agreeableness, can be seen increasing in long-term relationships.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The Big Five model has been subjected to considerable critical scrutiny in a number of published studies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] One prominent critic of the model has been Jack Block at the University of California, Berkeley.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In response to Block, the model was defended in a paper published by Costa and McCrae.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] This was followed by a number of published critical replies from Block.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The main criticism of the Big Five traits is that they do not explain enough of human personality.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Some psychologists feel it neglects other domains of personality, such as religiosity, manipulativeness/machiavellianism, honesty, sexiness/seductiveness, thrift, conservatism, masculinity/femininity, snobbishness, egotism, sense of humour, and risk-taking/thrill-seeking.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] McAdams has called the Big Five a "psychology of the stranger", because they refer to traits that are relatively easy to observe in a stranger; other aspects of personality that are more privately held or more context-dependent are excluded from the Big Five.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Block has pointed to several less-recognized but successful efforts to specify aspects of character not subsumed by the model.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] It has been argued the Big Five may account for as little as 56% of the normal personality trait sphere.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Studies indicate that the Big Five traits are not as powerful in predicting and explaining actual behaviour as the more fine-grained facets or primary traits.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] In his 1968 book *Personality and Assessment*, Walter Mischel asserted that personality instruments could not predict behavior with a correlation of more than 0.3.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Social psychologists like Mischel argued that attitudes and behavior were not stable, but varied with the situation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Scientists such as Mischel claimed predicting behavior from personality instruments was impossible.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] However, during the 1980s, emerging methodologies increasingly confirmed personality theories.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Though generally failing to predict single instances of behavior, researchers found that they could predict patterns of behavior by aggregating large numbers of observations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] As a result, correlations between personality and behavior increased substantially, and it became clear that "personality" did in fact exist.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The Big Five is not theory-driven but a statistical investigation of certain descriptors that tend to cluster.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Most measures of the FFM do not assess all of its maladaptive variants and therefore will not account for all of the components of a given personality disorder.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Measures to assess maladaptive FFM traits have been developed, including the Five Factor Model Personality Disorder scales, the Personality Inventory for ICD‐11, and the Personality Inventory for DSM‐5.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The model has been replicated in several languages, and the ICD and DSM models for personality disorders are shifting toward the FFM.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The five-factor model was among the first personality models in psychology derived from empirical research into natural-language data which found consistent correlations between the adjectives people use to describe themselves.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] Today, the five-factor model underlies most contemporary personality research, and the model has been described as one of the major breakthroughs of quantitative behavioural science.
[src:chief-executive-officer/big-five-personality-traits-p03] The five-factor structure has been confirmed by many subsequent studies across cultures and languages, which have replicated the original model and reported largely similar factors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A **board of directors** is a governing body that supervises the activities of a business, a nonprofit organization, or a government agency.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The powers, duties, and responsibilities of a board of directors are determined by government regulations (including the jurisdiction's corporate law) and the organization's own constitution and by-laws.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These authorities may specify the number of members of the board, how they are to be chosen, and how often they are to meet.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In an organization with voting members, the board is accountable to, and may be subordinate to, the organization's full membership, which usually elect the members of the board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In a stock corporation, non-executive directors are elected by the shareholders, and the board has ultimate responsibility for the management of the corporation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In nations with codetermination (such as Germany and Sweden), the workers of a corporation elect a set fraction of the board's members.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The board of directors appoints the chief executive officer of the corporation and sets out the overall strategic direction.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In corporations with dispersed ownership, the identification and nomination of directors (that shareholders vote for or against) are often done by the board itself, leading to a high degree of self-perpetuation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In a non-stock corporation with no general voting membership, the board is the supreme governing body of the institution, and its members are sometimes chosen by the board itself.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Other names include *board of directors and advisors*, *board of governors*, *board of managers*, *board of regents*, *board of trustees*, and *board of visitors*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It may also be called the *executive board*.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The legal responsibilities of boards and board members vary with the nature of the organization, and between jurisdictions.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] For companies with shares publicly listed for negotiation, these responsibilities are typically much more rigorous and complex than for those of other types.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Typically, the board chooses one of its members to be the *chairman* (often now called the "chair" or "chairperson"), who holds whatever title is specified in the by-laws or articles of association.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, in membership organizations, the members elect the president of the organization and the president becomes the board chair, unless the by-laws say otherwise.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The directors of an organization are the persons who are members of its board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Several specific terms categorize directors by the presence or absence of their other relationships to the organization.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Corporations may designate a former senior executive and ex-board member as an honorary board member, a position that does not carry any executive authority but represents recognition of the person's corporate governorship and performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] An inside director is a director who is also an employee, officer, chief executive, major shareholder, or someone similarly connected to the organization.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Inside directors represent the interests of the entity's stakeholders, and often have special knowledge of its inner workings, its financial or market position, and so on.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] An inside director who is employed as a manager or executive of the organization is sometimes referred to as an executive director (not to be confused with the title executive director sometimes used for the CEO position in some organizations).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Executive directors often have a specified area of responsibility in the organization, such as finance, marketing, human resources, or production.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] An outside director is a member of the board who is not otherwise employed by or engaged with the organization, and does not represent any of its stakeholders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A typical example is a director who is president of a firm in a different industry.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are not employees of the company or affiliated with it in any other way.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors bring outside experience and perspectives to the board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] For example, for a company that serves a domestic market only, the presence of CEOs from global multinational corporations as outside directors can help to provide insights on export and import opportunities and international trade options.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] One of the arguments for having outside directors is that they can keep a watchful eye on the inside directors and on the way the organization is run.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are unlikely to tolerate "insider dealing" between inside directors, as outside directors do not benefit from the company or organization.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are often useful in handling disputes between inside directors, or between shareholders and the board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] They are thought to be advantageous because they can be objective and present little risk of conflict of interest.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] On the other hand, they might lack familiarity with the specific issues connected to the organization's governance, and they might not know about the industry or sector in which the organization is operating.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Individual directors often serve on more than one board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This practice results in an interlocking directorate, where a relatively small number of individuals have significant influence over many important entities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This situation can have important corporate, social, economic, and legal consequences, and has been the subject of significant research.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The science of this process has been slow to develop due to the secretive nature of the way most companies run their boards, however some standardization is beginning to develop.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Some who are pushing for this standardization in the US are the National Association of Corporate Directors, McKinsey and The Board Group.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A board of directors conducts its meetings according to the rules and procedures contained in its governing documents.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These procedures may allow the board to conduct its business by conference call or other electronic means.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] They may also specify how a quorum is to be determined.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The responsibilities of a board of directors vary depending on the nature and type of business entity and the laws applying to the entity (see types of business entity).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] There are numerous types of business entities available throughout the world such as a corporation, limited liability company, cooperative, business trust, partnership, private limited company, and public limited company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Much of what has been written about boards of directors relates to boards of directors of business entities actively traded on public markets.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] More recently, however, material is becoming available for boards of private and closely held businesses including family businesses.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A board-only organization is one whose board is self-appointed, rather than being accountable to a base of members through elections; or in which the powers of the membership are extremely limited.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The amount of powers and authority delegated to the board depend on the bylaws and rules of the particular organization.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Some organizations place matters exclusively in the board's control while in others, the general membership retains full power and the board can only make recommendations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The setup of a board of directors varies widely across organizations and may include provisions that are applicable to corporations, in which the "shareholders" are the members of the organization.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A difference may be that the membership elects the officers of the organization, such as the president and the secretary, and the officers become members of the board in addition to the directors and retain those duties on the board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The directors may also be classified as officers in this situation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] There may also be ex-officio members of the board, or persons who are members due to another position that they hold.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These ex-officio members have all the same rights as the other board members.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Members of the board may be removed before their term is complete.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Details on how they can be removed are usually provided in the bylaws.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] If the bylaws do not contain such details, the section on disciplinary procedures in *Robert's Rules of Order* may be used.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In a publicly held company, directors are elected to represent and are legally obligated as fiduciaries to represent owners of the company—the shareholders/stockholders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In this capacity they establish policies and make decisions on issues such as whether there is a dividend and how much it is, stock options distributed to employees, and the hiring/firing and compensation of upper management.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Theoretically, the control of a company is divided between two bodies: the board of directors, and the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In practice, the amount of power exercised by the board varies with the type of company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In small private companies, the directors and the shareholders are normally the same people, and thus there is no real division of power.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Another feature of boards of directors in large public companies is that the board tends to have more *de facto* power.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Most shareholders do not attend shareholder meetings, but rather cast proxy votes via mail, phone, or internet, thus allowing the board to vote for them.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, proxy votes are not a total delegation of the voting power, as the board must vote the proxy shares as directed by their owner even when it contradicts the board's views.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In addition, many shareholders vote to accept all recommendations of the board rather than try to get involved in management, since each shareholder's power, as well as interest and information is so small.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Larger institutional investors also grant the board proxies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The large number of shareholders also makes it hard for them to organize.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, there have been moves recently to try to increase shareholder activism among both institutional investors and individuals with small shareholdings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A contrasting view is that in large public companies it is upper management and not boards that wield practical power, because boards delegate nearly all of their power to the top executive employees, adopting their recommendations almost without fail.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] As a practical matter, executives even choose the directors, with shareholders normally following management recommendations and voting for them.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In most cases, serving on a board is not a career unto itself.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] For major corporations, the board members are usually professionals or leaders in their field.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In the case of outside directors, they are often senior leaders of other organizations.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Nevertheless, board members often receive remunerations amounting to hundreds of thousands of dollars per year since they often sit on the boards of several companies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Inside directors are usually not paid for sitting on a board, but the duty is instead considered part of their larger job description.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Outside directors are usually paid for their services.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These remunerations vary between corporations, but usually consist of a yearly or monthly salary, additional compensation for each meeting attended, stock options, and various other benefits. such as travel, hotel and meal expenses for the board meetings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Academic research has identified different types of board directors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Their characteristics and experiences shape their role and performance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] For instance, directors with multiple mandates are often referred to as busy directors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Their monitoring performance is considered to be comparatively weak due to the limited time they can dedicate to this task.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Overconfident directors are found to pay higher premiums in corporate acquisitions and make worse takeover choices.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Locally rooted directors tend to be overrepresented and lack international experience, which can lead to lower valuations, especially in internationally oriented firms.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors' military experience is associated with rigorous monitoring and improved corporate governance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In some European and Asian countries, there are two separate boards, an executive board (or management board) for day-to-day business and a supervisory board (elected by the shareholders and employees) for supervising the executive board.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In these countries, the chairman of the supervisory board is equivalent to the chairman of a single-tier board, while the chairman of the management board is reckoned as the company's CEO or managing director.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These two roles are always held by different people.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This ensures a distinction between management by the executive board and governance by the supervisory board and allows for clear lines of authority.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The aim is to prevent a conflict of interest and too much power being concentrated in the hands of one person.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] There is a strong parallel here with the structure of government, where parliament (the supervisory board) oversees a cabinet of ministers (management officials, comprising the executive board) led by a head of government (CEO).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Board structures and procedures vary both within and among OECD countries.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Some countries have two-tier boards that separate the supervisory function and the management function into different bodies.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Such systems typically have a "supervisory board" composed of nonexecutive board members and a "management board" composed entirely of executives.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Other countries have "unitary" boards, which bring together executive and non-executive board members.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In some countries there is also an additional statutory body for audit purposes.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The OECD Principles are intended to be sufficiently general to apply to whatever board structure is charged with the functions of governing the enterprise and monitoring management.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The development of a separate board of directors to manage/govern/oversee a company has occurred incrementally and indefinitely over legal history.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Until the end of the 19th century, it seems to have been generally assumed that the general meeting (of all shareholders) was the supreme organ of a company, and that the board of directors merely acted as an agent of the company subject to the control of the shareholders in general meeting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The new approach did not secure immediate approval, but it was endorsed by the House of Lords in *Quin & Axtens v Salmon* [1909] AC 442 and has since received general acceptance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Under English law, successive versions of Table A have reinforced the norm that, unless the directors are acting contrary to the law or the provisions of the Articles, the powers of conducting the management and affairs of the company are vested in them.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It has been remarked that this development in the law was somewhat surprising at the time, as the relevant provisions in Table A (as it was then) seemed to contradict this approach rather than to endorse it.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The age of board members has become a notable trend across global stock exchanges, reflecting an increasingly older demographic in leadership roles.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] As of 2025, the average age of board members of companies listed on the Tokyo Stock Exchange stands at 62.2 years, while the United Kingdom reports an average of 60.1 years, Germany 59.3 years, South Korea 59 years, and Hong Kong 54.9 years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] New York Stock Exchange companies exhibit the highest average age, at 62.9 years.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In response to this aging trend, some firms, particularly those in entertainment and trend-driven sectors, have actively sought to appoint younger board members.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] An example is Sanrio, the Japanese company behind the Hello Kitty franchise, which reduced the average age of its board from 68 years in 2020 to 51 years by 2024, signaling a deliberate intergenerational shift in governance.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In most legal systems, the appointment and removal of directors is voted upon by the shareholders in general meeting or through a proxy statement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] For publicly traded companies in the U.S., the directors which are available to vote on are largely selected by either the board as a whole or a nominating committee.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Shareholder nominations can only occur at the general meeting itself or through the prohibitively expensive process of mailing out ballots separately; in May 2009 the SEC proposed a new rule allowing shareholders meeting certain criteria to add nominees to the proxy statement.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In countries with co-determination, a fixed fraction of the board is elected by the corporation's workers.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors may also leave office by resignation or death.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In some legal systems, directors may also be removed by a resolution of the remaining directors (in some countries they may only do so "with cause"; in others the power is unrestricted).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Some jurisdictions also permit the board of directors to appoint directors, either to fill a vacancy which arises on resignation or death, or as an addition to the existing directors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In practice, it can be quite difficult to remove a director by a resolution in general meeting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In many legal systems, the director has a right to receive special notice of any resolution to remove them; the company must often supply a copy of the proposal to the director, who is usually entitled to be heard by the meeting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The director may require the company to circulate any representations that they wish to make.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Furthermore, the director's contract of service will usually entitle them to compensation if they are removed, and may often include a generous "golden parachute" which also acts as a deterrent to removal.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A 2010 study examined how corporate shareholders voted in director elections in the United States.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It found that directors received fewer votes from shareholders when their companies performed poorly, had excess CEO compensation, or had poor shareholder protection.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Also, directors received fewer votes when they did not regularly attend board meetings or received negative recommendations from a proxy advisory firm.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The study also shows that companies often improve their corporate governance by removing poison pills or classified boards and by reducing excessive CEO pay after their directors receive low shareholder support.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Board accountability to shareholders is a recurring issue.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In September 2010, *The New York Times* noted that several directors who had overseen companies which had failed in the 2008 financial crisis had found new positions as directors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The SEC sometimes imposes a ban (a "D&O bar") on serving on a board as part of its fraud cases, and one of these was upheld in 2013.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The exercise by the board of directors of its powers usually occurs in board meetings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Most legal systems require sufficient notice to be given to all directors of these meetings, and that a quorum must be present before any business may be conducted.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In most common law countries, the powers of the board are vested in the board as a whole, and not in the individual directors.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, in instances an individual director may still bind the company by their acts by virtue of their ostensible authority (see also: the rule in *Turquand's Case*).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Because directors exercise control and management over the organization, but organizations are (in theory) run for the benefit of the shareholders, the law imposes strict duties on directors in relation to the exercise of their duties.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The duties imposed on directors are fiduciary duties, similar to those that the law imposes on those in similar positions of trust: agents and trustees.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The duties apply to each director separately, while the powers apply to the board jointly.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Also, the duties are owed to the company itself, and not to any other entity.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This does not mean that directors can never stand in a fiduciary relationship to the individual shareholders; they may well have such a duty in certain circumstances.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors must exercise their powers for a proper purpose.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] While in many instances an improper purpose is readily evident, such as a director looking to enrich themselves or divert an investment opportunity to a relative, such breaches usually involve a breach of the director's duty to act in good faith.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Greater difficulties arise where the director, while acting in good faith, is serving a purpose that is not regarded by the law as proper.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The seminal authority in the United Kingdom in relation to what amounts to a proper purpose is the Supreme Court decision in Eclairs Group Ltd v JKX Oil & Gas plc (2015).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The case concerned the powers of directors under the articles of association of the company to disenfranchise voting rights attached to shares for failure to properly comply with notice served on the shareholders.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Prior to that case the leading authority was *Howard Smith Ltd v Ampol Ltd* [1974] AC 821.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The case concerned the power of the directors to issue new shares.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It was alleged that the directors had issued many new shares purely to deprive a particular shareholder of his voting majority.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] If so, the mere fact that an incidental result (even if it was a desired consequence) was that a shareholder lost their majority, or a takeover bid was defeated, this would not itself make the share issue improper.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] But if the sole purpose was to destroy a voting majority, or block a takeover bid, that would be an improper purpose.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Not all jurisdictions recognised the "proper purpose" duty as separate from the "good faith" duty however.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors cannot, without the consent of the company, fetter their discretion in relation to the exercise of their powers, and cannot bind themselves to vote in a particular way at future board meetings.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This is so even if there is no improper motive or purpose, and no personal advantage to the director.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This does not mean, however, that the board cannot agree to the company entering into a contract which binds the company to a certain course, even if certain actions in that course will require further board approval, such as issuing bonds.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The company remains bound, but the directors retain the discretion to vote against taking the future actions (although that may involve a breach by the company of the contract that the board previously approved).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] As fiduciaries, the directors may not put themselves in a position where their interests and duties conflict with the duties that they owe to the company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The law takes the view that good faith must not only be done, but must be manifestly seen to be done, and zealously patrols the conduct of directors in this regard; and will not allow directors to escape liability by asserting that their decisions were in fact well founded.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] By definition, where a director enters into a transaction with a company, there is a conflict between the director's interest (to enrich themselves with the transaction) and their duty to the company (to ensure that the company gets as much as it can out of the transaction).
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In some places, this rule is so strictly enforced that, even where the conflict of interest or conflict of duty is purely hypothetical, the directors can be forced to disgorge all personal gains arising from it.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] "A corporate body can only act by agents, and it is, of course, the duty of those agents so to act as best to promote the interests of the corporation whose affairs they are conducting.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Such agents have duties to discharge of a fiduciary nature towards their principal.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] , with the interests of those whom he is bound to protect...
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, in many jurisdictions the members of the company are permitted to ratify transactions which would otherwise fall foul of this principle.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It is also largely accepted in most jurisdictions that this principle can be overridden in the company's constitution.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] In many countries, there is also a statutory duty to declare interests in relation to any transactions, and the director can be fined for failing to make disclosure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors must not, without the informed consent of the company, use for their own profit the company's assets, opportunities, or information.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This prohibition is much less flexible than the prohibition against the transactions with the company, and attempts to circumvent it using provisions in the articles have met with limited success.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] And accordingly, the directors were required to disgorge the profits that they made, and the shareholders received their windfall.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The decision has been followed in several subsequent cases, and is now regarded as settled law.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Directors cannot compete directly with the company without a conflict of interest arising.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Similarly, they should not act as directors of competing companies, as their duties to each company would then conflict with each other.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Traditionally, the level of care and skill which has to be demonstrated by a director has been framed largely with reference to the non-executive director.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, a more modern approach has since developed, and in *Dorchester Finance Co Ltd v Stebbing* [1989] BCLC 498 the court held that the rule in *Equitable Fire* related only to skill, and not to diligence.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This was a dual subjective and objective test, and one deliberately pitched at a higher level.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] More recently, it has been suggested that both the tests of skill and diligence should be assessed objectively and subjectively; in the United Kingdom, the statutory provisions relating to directors' duties in the new Companies Act 2006 have been codified on this basis.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Historically, directors' duties have been owed almost exclusively to the company and its members, and the board was expected to exercise its powers for the financial benefit of the company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] However, more recently there have been attempts to "soften" the position, and provide for more scope for directors to act as good corporate citizens.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This represents a considerable departure from the traditional notion that directors' duties are owed only to the company.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The changes have therefore been the subject of some criticism.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] The adoption of technology that facilitates the meeting preparation and execution of directors continues to grow.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Board directors are increasingly leveraging this technology to communicate and collaborate within a secure environment to access meeting materials, communicate with each other, and execute their governance responsibilities.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] This trend is particularly acute in the United States where a robust market of early adopters garnered acceptance of board software by organizations resulting in higher penetration of the board portal services in the region.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Most companies have weak mechanisms for bringing the voice of society into the board room.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] They rely on personalities who were not appointed for their understanding of societal issues.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Often they give limited focus (both through time and financial resource) to issues of corporate responsibility and sustainability.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] A social board has society designed into its structure.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] It elevates the voice of society through specialist appointments to the board and mechanisms that empower innovation from within the organisation.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Social boards align themselves with themes that are important to society.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] These may include measuring worker pay ratios, linking personal social and environmental objectives to remuneration, integrated reporting, fair tax and B-Corp certification.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] Social boards recognise that they are part of society and that they require more than a licence to operate to succeed.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] They balance short-term shareholder pressure against long-term value creation, managing the business for a plurality of stakeholders including employees, shareholders, supply chains and civil society.
[src:chief-executive-officer/board-of-directors] India has no legislative equivalent to Sarbanes–Oxley Act (given below), though Clause 49 of the SEBI Listing Agreement provides relevant rules.
